        'slug' => 'mt-romelo-buruwisan-falls-siniloan-overnight-trek',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Romelo in Siniloan, Laguna is the entry-level overnight trek with a waterfall payoff. Here is the trail, the camp, and what to bring for the mud.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Romelo sits in Siniloan, Laguna, at the edge of the Sierra Madre. It is one of the older training mountains in the south, the kind of climb where a lot of Manila trekkers logged their first overnight before they moved on to bigger trails. The mountain itself is not the draw. The waterfalls that string along the base, Buruwisan, Batya-Batya, Sampaloc, and Lansones, are what pull people up the trail.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a one-night camp at the Buruwisan campsite, with a side trip down to the falls in the afternoon and a slow walk out the next morning. The trail is shorter than most overnight climbs in Luzon, around three hours up, but it carries a reputation for mud that earned it the trail-name "Famous Mudslide."</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Macatad in Siniloan, near the Magdapio bridge. Register at the barangay hall, pay the small fee, and hire a guide before the climb. The trail begins on a wide cogon ridge, with the sun fully on you for the first hour. The slope is gentle but the surface is loose dirt that turns into a clay slide after rain.</p>
<h3>The Mudslide Section</h3>
<p>The middle third of the trail is the famous slide. After any rainfall, the path becomes a smooth chute of brown clay that the early trekkers have polished into a near-slick surface. Going up takes the use of branches, roots, and the help of the trekkers ahead. Coming down is its own kwento, the locals slide down on their backsides and laugh; first-timers tend to fall four or five times.</p>
<h3>Buruwisan Campsite</h3>
<p>The camp sits in a small clearing near the head of Buruwisan Falls. The water sound is constant through the night, the canopy is thick, and the air is cool even in summer. Pitch the tent on the higher ground, the lower spots flood when the night rains come in.</p>
<h2>The Falls Side Trip</h2>
<p>From camp, a short and very steep descent leads down to the base of Buruwisan Falls. The drop is around 30 meters, into a wide pool you can swim in. Locals know the route to two more falls, Batya-Batya and Sampaloc, that are 20 to 40 minutes farther downstream. If you have the afternoon and a guide, take all three. If not, Buruwisan alone is the photo and the swim that pays back the climb.</p>
<h3>The Climb Down to Buruwisan</h3>
<p>This is the technical part of the trip, not the climb up the mountain. The descent uses fixed ropes that the local guides maintain. Wear gloves, the rope burn is real if you slide. Trail runners with good grip handle the rocks better than open sandals.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent and ground sheet, the campsite is mossy and damp</li>
<li>Headlamp, the canopy blocks any moonlight</li>
<li>Trail-running shoes with deep lugs, the mud is unforgiving on flat soles</li>
<li>Gloves for the rope descent to the falls</li>
<li>A change of clothes sealed in a dry bag</li>
<li>Three liters of water for the climb, the camp has a spring nearby for refills</li>
<li>Trash bag, all rubbish has to come down with you</li>
<li>Light insect repellent, the evening mosquitoes are persistent</li>
</ul>
<h2>What to Skip</h2>
<p>Skip the white shirts, the clay will not come out. Skip the heavy DSLR setup, the descent to the falls is a hands-on scramble and a phone camera is enough. Skip the cotton socks, they soak through and stay wet for the whole trip.</p>
<h2>Getting to Siniloan</h2>
<p>From Manila, ride a bus from Cubao or EDSA-Buendia to Sta. Cruz, Laguna, then transfer to a jeepney bound for Siniloan. Total ride is around four hours. From the Siniloan town proper, a tricycle to Brgy. Macatad jump-off is a short ride. <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> and DLTB both run the southern Laguna route. A private car parked at the barangay hall is fine for an overnight; the locals watch the cars for a small tip.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to May are the cooler, drier months and the safest for the climb. The mud is still there, just not as deep. June to October the trail becomes a serious slide and the falls run heavier; experienced trekkers prefer this season for the water, beginners should wait for the dry months. Avoid Holy Week, the camp gets crowded enough that the local barangay sometimes caps daily entries.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay Before or After</h2>
<p>Most groups skip the overnight stay and treat the trip as a Manila-to-Manila weekend. If you want to stay over and explore Laguna further, the Pansol and San Pablo area has hot-spring pools and small inns. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729454-Laguna_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a> or <a href="https://www.agoda.com/city/laguna-ph.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Agoda</a>.</p>
<p>Romelo is the kind of mountain that gets dismissed by serious climbers and still earns a soft spot. The mud is the test, the falls are the reward, and the kwento on the way down is what most groups remember a year later.</p>
