        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Talamitam sits along the Nasugbu highway in Batangas, around 50 kilometers south of Tagaytay. It is the small, cogon-grass mountain that travelers spot from the road on the way to Nasugbu beach trips and ask, what is that, can we climb it. The answer is yes, and you can do the climb in a single morning if you start before sunrise.</p>
<p>The summit is 630 meters, the trail is around two and a half hours up, and the entire walk is on open grass with almost no tree cover. That last detail is the one that makes or breaks the day. Climb early or pay for it in heat.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is on the side of the Nasugbu highway in Brgy. Bayabasan. Register at the barangay tourism table near the road, hire a guide, and start walking through the cattle farm at the base of the mountain. The first kilometer is flat, crossing the Buntot Palos river twice; in the dry months the water is shallow and rock-hopping works. The wet season makes the crossings deeper.</p>
<h3>The Cogon Ascent</h3>
<p>Past the second river crossing, the trail starts to climb. The grade is steady, not steep, but the cogon grass closes in on the path and the sun hits you with no break. By 8 a.m. the upper slopes feel like a hairdryer. Mark each false summit, the ridge has three of them, and the actual summit is the fourth knob.</p>
<h3>At the Summit</h3>
<p>The peak is a wide grass clearing with a view of Mt. Batulao to the southwest and the West Philippine Sea beyond. On clear mornings you can also see Mt. Pico de Loro and the Maragondon range. The summit fits maybe 20 trekkers comfortably; on weekends from December to March it is fuller than that.</p>
<h2>Why Early Starts Matter</h2>
<p>Talamitam has no tree cover. Every meter up is exposed sun. Climbers who start at 5 a.m. are off the summit by 8 a.m. and back at the highway by 10 a.m., before the worst of the heat. Climbers who start at 8 a.m. finish in the noon sun and end up with a headache and a sunburn. The rule on this mountain is simple, start in the dark.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Headlamp for the pre-dawn start</li>
<li>Trail runners or hiking shoes, the slope is grassy but loose</li>
<li>A wide-brim hat or buff for the full sun</li>
<li>Long-sleeve sun shirt, sunscreen on the face and hands</li>
<li>Two liters of water, three on a warm day</li>
<li>Electrolyte sachets, the heat sweats out the salt fast</li>
<li>A light packed breakfast for the summit</li>
<li>Cash for the registration and guide fee</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Manila Day-Trip Flow</h2>
<p>The cleanest plan is to leave Manila at 2 a.m., reach Bayabasan by 4:30 a.m., start the climb at 5 a.m., reach the summit by 7:30 a.m., descend by 10 a.m., and grab a late breakfast in Nasugbu or Tagaytay on the way home. The whole trip wraps up by lunchtime. If you want to extend, combine the climb with a Pico de Loro Cove afternoon or a Tagaytay bulalo lunch.</p>
<h3>Getting to Bayabasan</h3>
<p>By car, take the CAVITEX-Kawit exit, then the Aguinaldo highway to Tagaytay, and the Nasugbu highway down. Bayabasan is around 25 minutes past the Magallanes town proper. By bus, ride a Nasugbu-bound DLTB or Erjohn-Almark bus from Buendia and tell the conductor to drop you at Brgy. Bayabasan in Nasugbu. The bus drops you on the highway in front of the jump-off.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat After</h2>
<p>Tagaytay is the obvious lunch stop on the way home. The bulalo strip in Mahogany Market is the standard order, but the longer kwento from regular Talamitam climbers is to stop at any of the carinderias along the Nasugbu highway for tapsilog, then push for the longer Tagaytay lunch only if the group still has appetite. The first food after a sun-heavy climb tends to taste better than the planned destination.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through March are the dry, cool months and the safest for the climb. April and May the sun becomes punishing even with a pre-dawn start. June to October the trail closes during heavy rain because the river crossings rise, but the cogon ridge becomes green again and the photos are softer. Weekday climbs are quietest; the summit can pack twenty groups on a Saturday in January.</p>
<p>Talamitam is short enough to be a single-morning trip and exposed enough to teach you to respect the Philippine sun. Either way, the kwento at the summit with the breeze pushing through the grass is what brings most climbers back to do it again.</p>
