        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Sembrano stands at 745 meters along the eastern shore of Laguna de Bay, in the town of Pililla, Rizal. The mountain is part of the same range that includes Mt. Sembrano, Mt. Maynuba, and the Tanay highlands. From the summit, on a clear day, you can see the full sweep of Laguna de Bay, the Talim Island silhouette, and the Sierra Madre wall to the east. The climb itself is one of the calmer day hikes near Manila, with a forested middle section that gives a real break from the sun.</p>
<p>The trail is around three hours up, three hours down, with a small lunch stop at the summit. Most groups treat it as a Saturday-only trip from Quezon City or Antipolo, then a leisurely lunch in Tanay on the drive back.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Malaya in Pililla, near the foot of the famous Pililla wind farm road. Register at the barangay hall, pay the day-hike fee, and hire a local guide before the climb. The first 30 minutes is a flat walk through farm plots and a small mango grove, easy and shaded.</p>
<h3>The Forest Section</h3>
<p>Past the farm, the trail enters a secondary forest that runs for around an hour. This is the cooler part of the climb. The path is rooty, mossy in places, and the canopy holds the heat off. Take this part slow, the soft trail is the kind of walking that pays back the early start.</p>
<h3>The Cogon Ridge</h3>
<p>The forest opens to a cogon ridge that runs along the spine of the mountain for the last 45 minutes to the summit. The view of Laguna de Bay opens up on the left, the Sierra Madre on the right, and the trail is a clean walk on grass. Photos here look more like the Cordilleras than Rizal.</p>
<h3>At the Summit</h3>
<p>The peak is a clearing with a wooden marker and a 360-degree view. Talim Island in the lake is the closest landmark; on a clear morning Makiling is faintly visible across the lake to the south. The summit fits around 30 trekkers comfortably. There is a smaller false peak that some groups stop at by mistake; check with the guide that you are at the actual summit before turning back.</p>
<h2>The Pililla Wind Farm Side Stop</h2>
<p>The Pililla wind farm is on the same road as the Sembrano jump-off. The viewing deck for the turbines is free and the road up is paved. Combine the climb with a wind-farm stop on the way back; the turbines turn slowly against the Laguna de Bay backdrop and the photos there are quiet. The deck has a small cafeteria for halo-halo and grilled corn.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners or light hiking shoes, the forest section has roots</li>
<li>Two liters of water, no spring on the trail</li>
<li>A light buff for the cogon ridge, the sun there is direct</li>
<li>Light pack lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Cash for the registration, guide, and the wind-farm cafeteria</li>
<li>Rain jacket from June to October</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Pililla</h2>
<p>By car, take the Marikina-Infanta Highway from Antipolo through Cogeo, Sampaloc, Tanay, and into Pililla. The drive from Quezon City is around two hours in light traffic. By jeepney, ride from Cogeo to Tanay, then transfer to a Pililla-bound jeep, and tell the driver to drop you near the wind farm road. From the wind farm junction, a tricycle ride to the Malaya jump-off is short.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat After</h2>
<p>Tanay is the food stop on the drive home. The town has a few longtime carinderias along the highway that serve calderetang kambing and tilapia from Laguna de Bay. Two of the bigger pasalubong stops are between Tanay and Antipolo, with suman and kakanin laid out fresh in the afternoons. If you have not eaten at any of the lakeside grill stands in Tanay, this is the trip to try one.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the safest. The cogon ridge gets exposed sun on the descent so an early start helps. June to October the trail is muddier and the river crossings on the descent can run higher, but the forest section is at its greenest. Weekend climbs are not as crowded as Talamitam or Batulao; Sembrano is the lesser-known sibling of those two and the trail stays comfortable.</p>
<p>Sembrano is the kind of day hike that does not appear in many top-ten lists and earns a quiet following. The forest, the ridge, the lake view, and the wind farm on the way home make for a long but easy day. Tara, this is the climb to add when you are tired of the busier southern peaks.</p>
