        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Maynuba in Tanay pairs a forested climb with the Cabuyao Twin Falls below. Here is the trail, the pool stop, and the long Tanay drive home.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Maynuba is one of the lesser-known peaks in the Tanay highlands, sitting in the same general area as Mt. Daraitan and Mt. Lubo. The mountain itself is not the only draw, the standard plan also drops down to the Cabuyao Twin Falls behind the ridge, a cold pool with two narrow spillways above it. Total day, mountain plus falls, is around eight hours of moving time. Bring a packed lunch and an early-start mindset and the trip works as a single Saturday.</p>
<p>This is the climb that local groups recommend after Daraitan but before the bigger Sierra Madre traverses. The trail has variety, a real summit view, and a swim at the end. Tara, here is the kwento by section.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Cuyambay in Tanay, the same general area as Daraitan, though a different barangay road. Register at the barangay hall, hire the local guide, and walk the first 30 minutes through farm plots. The trail then climbs through a secondary forest that holds the cool air well into the morning.</p>
<h3>The Ridge to Maynuba</h3>
<p>The middle section is a long ridge with periodic views of the Sierra Madre wall on the east side. Wild bamboo lines the trail and the bird sounds carry through the canopy. The grade is moderate, not punishing, and the rest stops have flat patches that work for a 10-minute break.</p>
<h3>At the Maynuba Summit</h3>
<p>The summit sits at around 670 meters. The view opens to the east, into the Sierra Madre, and to the southwest, back across the Tanay highlands toward Laguna de Bay. The peak is small, a tight clearing with one bench. Photos and a quick snack, then the descent toward Cabuyao Falls.</p>
<h2>The Descent to Cabuyao Twin Falls</h2>
<p>The route to the falls drops sharply behind the summit. The path is rooty, sometimes muddy, with two fixed-rope sections where the slope steepens. Take this part slow. The falls open into a narrow ravine with a wide pool at the base, fed by two parallel spillways from the upper river. The water is cold, the pool depth is around chest-high in the middle, and the locals say it is safe to swim across.</p>
<h3>The Pool</h3>
<p>Lunch at the falls is the standard plan. A bench of flat rocks works for a packed meal. Swim, eat, dry off, and start the climb out by 1 p.m. so you make the descent back to the village before the late-afternoon sun. The falls are loud enough that conversation gets pushed across the pool; keep the group close.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners with deep lugs, the descent is rooty and muddy</li>
<li>Light gloves for the rope sections</li>
<li>Quick-dry shirt and shorts, the swim is part of the plan</li>
<li>A change of dry clothes in a sealed dry bag</li>
<li>Two liters of water, three is safer</li>
<li>Pack lunch, the falls have no food vendors</li>
<li>Headlamp, the descent back can run into late afternoon shadow</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the post-hike merienda</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Tanay Drive Home</h2>
<p>From Cuyambay back to Manila is around two and a half hours through Sampaloc and Antipolo. Pile up the merienda stops on the way back. The roadside vendors along the Marikina-Infanta Highway sell suman, kakanin, and binatog from late afternoon. The Tanay public market is also worth a 20-minute stop for fresh tilapia and Laguna de Bay snails.</p>
<h2>Getting to Cuyambay</h2>
<p>By car, take the Marcos Highway from Marikina up to Sampaloc, then Cogeo, Antipolo, and Tanay. From the Tanay town proper, follow the road toward Daraitan and turn off at Cuyambay. By jeepney, ride from Cogeo Gate 2 to Tanay, then transfer to a Cuyambay-bound jeep. Total ride from Cubao is around three hours with light traffic.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the safer months. The trail is drier and the river crossings are easier. June to October the falls run heavier and the photos are dramatic, but the descent gets slippery and the guide may refuse to do the rope sections in heavy rain. Weekday climbs are quietest; the falls can fill up on Saturdays in summer.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most groups treat the climb as a day trip from Manila. If you want to extend, Tanay has guesthouses and farm stays along the Marcos Highway. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895125-Tanay_Rizal_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Maynuba is the trek that surprises first-timers. The mountain pays you back with a forest, a ridge, and a cold pool at the bottom of the descent. For a Saturday plan that fits in a single day, it is one of the better Tanay choices.</p>
