        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Marami in Maragondon, Cavite is the long but rewarding day hike with the Silyang Bato rock chair at the summit. Here is the trail and the heat plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Marami sits in the Maragondon range in Cavite, the same general highland that holds Pico de Loro and Mt. Palay-Palay. The mountain is best known for Silyang Bato, a natural stone formation at the summit that looks like a chair carved out of a single boulder. The climb is long, around five to six hours up, two to three hours down, on a sun-exposed trail with cogon grass for most of the middle section.</p>
<p>Marami is the kind of mountain that gets done in a single very long day from Manila by groups who start at 4 a.m. and do not get home until late evening. It is not for first-timers, but for trekkers who have a few day hikes logged, it is one of the better summit pay-offs in southern Luzon.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Ramirez in Magallanes, Cavite, the standard side, or at Talipusngo in Maragondon, the alternate side. Most groups use the Ramirez entry because the trail is better marked. Register at the barangay hall, hire the local guide, and start the climb on a flat farm road that runs for the first kilometer.</p>
<h3>The Cogon Section</h3>
<p>Past the farm, the trail climbs through wide cogon-grass slopes for around two hours. The grass is shoulder-high in places, the sun is direct, and the wind tends to drop in the middle of the day. Most heat exhaustion incidents on Marami happen here. Pre-dawn start is the only sane plan.</p>
<h3>The Boulder Trail</h3>
<p>The upper third of the climb runs through a boulder field, with the trail weaving between large rock outcrops. This section is shaded and cooler, a real break from the cogon. Watch the footing, the rocks are loose in places.</p>
<h3>At the Summit</h3>
<p>The summit holds Silyang Bato, the stone chair. The view from the chair opens to the West Philippine Sea on one side, to the Maragondon range on the other, and on clear days you can see Mt. Pico de Loro to the southwest. The chair fits one person comfortably, two if you are friends. Most groups queue politely for the summit photo.</p>
<h2>Why Marami Needs a Heat Plan</h2>
<p>The cogon section has no shade. The boulder field is the only break in the middle of the climb. Returning across the cogon in the late afternoon is the riskier hour, the heat builds even in the dry months. The fix is to start at 4 a.m. so you are off the cogon by 8 a.m., reach the summit by 10 a.m., and back across the cogon by 1 p.m. before the worst hour. Climbers who start at 7 a.m. routinely cramp on the descent.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Three liters of water, four on warm days</li>
<li>Electrolyte sachets, a real necessity here</li>
<li>Trail-running shoes with grip for the boulders</li>
<li>Long-sleeve sun shirt and a wide-brim hat</li>
<li>Sunscreen and lip balm with SPF</li>
<li>Headlamp for the pre-dawn start</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the late lunch in Maragondon</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Magallanes</h2>
<p>From Manila, by car, take the CAVITEX-Kawit exit, then the Aguinaldo highway south through Imus, Dasmarinas, Silang, and into Magallanes town. From Magallanes, follow the road to Brgy. Ramirez. By bus, ride a Saint Anthony of Padua or Erjohn-Almark bus from PITX to Magallanes, then a tricycle to the Ramirez jump-off. Total trip from Manila is around three and a half hours by car, four by bus.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat After</h2>
<p>Maragondon town has carinderias along the main road for tapa, longganisa, and pork sinigang. The Aguinaldo Shrine and the Bonifacio Trial House are both in the area if you want a small history stop on the way home. For a longer rest, Tagaytay is around 45 minutes away and the bulalo strip there is the standard descent meal.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to March are the dry, cool months and the only safe window for first-time Marami climbers. April and May the heat is dangerous, even the local guides will refuse afternoon climbs. June to October the cogon turns green and the photos soften, but the trail becomes slick and the rivers near the jump-off rise. Weekday climbs are quietest; the summit chair has a queue on weekends from January to March.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most groups do Marami as a single-day trip. If you want to extend, Tagaytay or Nasugbu are the easy overnight bases. Compare Tagaytay options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g676539-Tagaytay_Cavite_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Marami earns its long-day reputation. The cogon is the test, the chair is the payoff, and the heat on the descent is what most climbers remember a week later. Plan the start time, the water, and the lunch carefully and the mountain rewards you with one of the better photo spots in Cavite.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Marami and Silyang Bato: Maragondon Cavite Hike | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY day-hike plan for Mt. Marami and Silyang Bato in Maragondon, Cavite. Cogon trail, boulder field, summit chair, transport, and the heat plan.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Marami, Silyang Bato, Maragondon, Cavite, Day Hike',
