    // 6. MT. HAPUNANG BANOI AND MT. BINACAYAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2014/10/mt-hapunang-banoi.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Hapunang Banoi and Mt. Binacayan: A Rodriguez Two-Peak Day',
        'slug' => 'mt-hapunang-banoi-binacayan-rodriguez-two-peak-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Hapunang Banoi and Mt. Binacayan share the same Rodriguez jump-off as Mt. Pamitinan. Here is the trail plan that puts both peaks in a single day.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Hapunang Banoi and Mt. Binacayan are the two limestone peaks that flank Mt. Pamitinan in Rodriguez, Rizal. The three mountains share the same jump-off at the Wawa River and the same general trail system. Most groups take on one peak at a time, but a strong day-hiker pair can do Banoi and Binacayan in a single day, with the Pamitinan climb saved for a separate trip. The kwento here is the limestone karst, the sharp ridges, and the views down to the Wawa Dam.</p>
<p>The trails are short but technically on the harder side, with hand-on-rock scrambling on both peaks. Wear gloves, bring trail runners with grip, and start early.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. San Rafael in Rodriguez, near the Wawa Dam staging area. Register at the barangay tourism table, hire the local guide, and choose your peak order. Most groups go Hapunang Banoi in the morning, descend to the river for lunch, and Binacayan in the afternoon. The Binacayan side is shorter but steeper.</p>
<h3>Hapunang Banoi Ascent</h3>
<p>Hapunang Banoi sits at around 632 meters. The trail climbs through limestone karst, with sections where you pull yourself up using the rock itself. Wear gloves, the limestone is sharp and the cuts are minor but they sting. The summit is a small clearing with a view across the Wawa River to Pamitinan and the Sierra Madre.</p>
<h3>Binacayan Ascent</h3>
<p>Binacayan sits at around 425 meters. The trail is shorter, the ascent is steeper, and the final 100 meters use fixed ropes on a near-vertical rock face. The summit is a flat boulder with a wide view of the dam, the river, and the Marikina Valley behind it. Combined with Banoi in one day, the total moving time is around six to seven hours.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Gloves, the limestone is sharp</li>
<li>Trail runners with deep lugs, the slope is loose in places</li>
<li>Three liters of water, no spring on either trail</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the river break</li>
<li>Headlamp, the late descent can run into shadow</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the merienda at the dam</li>
</ul>
<h2>The River Lunch Break</h2>
<p>Between the two climbs, drop down to the Wawa River for lunch. The water is cool, the rocks are flat enough to sit on, and a small lugaw vendor sets up at the staging area on weekends. Soak the feet in the river for 30 minutes, the second peak feels lighter after.</p>
<h2>Getting to Wawa</h2>
<p>By car, take Marcos Highway from Marikina, exit at Cogeo Gate 2, and follow the road to Rodriguez town proper. From Rodriguez, the road to Wawa Dam is signposted. By jeepney, ride from Cubao to Montalban, then transfer to a jeepney bound for Wawa. Total trip from Manila is around two hours.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the safest for the rope sections. The limestone gets slick after rain and the guides may refuse the Binacayan rope face in heavy weather. June to October the trails are open between rains but the rock work is harder. Weekday climbs are quietest, the trail can fill up on Saturdays.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most groups do Hapunang Banoi and Binacayan as a Manila day trip. For a relaxed plan, stay overnight in Antipolo and tackle the climb the next morning. Antipolo has a few small inns near the city center. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895048-Antipolo_Rizal_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>The two-peak Wawa loop is the kind of trip that suits trekkers who like rock work and short approach trails. The limestone, the rope sections, and the river lunch in between make for a full day with variety. Save Pamitinan for a separate weekend, the three peaks in one day is a tougher itinerary that the local guides discourage.</p>
