    // 8. TARAK RIDGE, MARIVELES BATAAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2007/01/tarak-ridge-mariveles-1130.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Tarak Ridge, Mariveles Bataan: An Overnight Climb with a Manila Bay View',
        'slug' => 'tarak-ridge-mariveles-bataan-overnight-climb-bay-view',
        'excerpt' => 'Tarak Ridge in Mariveles, Bataan is the ridge climb with an open campsite and a view of Manila Bay. Here is the trail plan and the Bataan loop home.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tarak Ridge is the front shoulder of the Mariveles range in Bataan, sitting at around 1,130 meters above Manila Bay. The mountain belongs to the Mariveles Dome system, which also includes Mt. Mariveles and Mt. Pantingan. Tarak is the most accessible of the three, the overnight climb that lets you camp on the ridge with the bay below and the city lights at night. The standard plan is a Saturday-afternoon climb, a sunset on the ridge, a night camp, and a Sunday-morning descent.</p>
<p>Total moving time is around seven hours up, four hours down. The climb is rated moderate, not technical, but the river crossings and the cogon ridge demand a heat plan and an early start on the descent.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Alas-asin in Mariveles, on the Bataan coast at the south end of the peninsula. Register at the barangay hall, hire a local guide, and start the climb on a flat farm trail along the Alas-asin River. The first 90 minutes follows the river, crossing it three or four times. Wear shoes you can wet, the crossings are shin-deep in the dry season.</p>
<h3>The Assault</h3>
<p>Past the last river crossing, the trail climbs steeply through a secondary forest. The grade is steady, no rope work, but the heart rate stays up. Around the three-hour mark, the trail emerges onto a cogon ridge with the first view of Manila Bay across to Cavite and Bataan.</p>
<h3>Papaya River Campsite</h3>
<p>Most groups camp at Papaya River, around 30 minutes below the actual ridge. The site has a water source, flat ground, and tree cover. From the camp, a 30-minute push reaches Tarak Ridge itself, the open clearing on the lip of the cliff.</p>
<h3>Tarak Ridge</h3>
<p>The ridge clearing is wide enough for a dozen tents. The view sweeps across Manila Bay, Cavite to the east, and on a clear night the lights of Manila itself spread along the horizon. Sunset here is the standard photo. Sunrise the next morning lights up the Mariveles Dome behind you.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent with a strong rain fly, the ridge wind is real</li>
<li>Warm layer, the ridge can drop to 18 degrees at night</li>
<li>Trail-running shoes that handle wet rocks for the river crossings</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>Three liters of water for the climb, the Papaya River refills</li>
<li>Stove and food for one dinner and one breakfast</li>
<li>Light rain layer, the ridge weather changes fast</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the post-climb meal in Mariveles</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Mariveles</h2>
<p>From Manila, ride a Genesis or Bataan Transit bus from Cubao or PITX bound for Mariveles, and drop at the Alas-asin junction. By car, take NLEX-SCTEX through Subic, then the Roman Highway south through Bagac, Morong, and into Mariveles. Total trip is around four hours by car, five by bus. The Mariveles town proper is on the Roman Highway, Alas-asin is a 15-minute tricycle ride from there.</p>
<h2>The Bataan Loop Option</h2>
<p>For groups making a weekend of it, the Bataan loop adds a Sunday-afternoon stop at the Pawikan Conservation Center in Morong on the drive home. The center hatches sea turtle eggs and releases the hatchlings during the season (November to February). The drive from Mariveles to Morong is around 90 minutes along the coast.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to April are the dry, cool months and the safer climbing window. The river crossings are shallow and the ridge weather is stable. May the heat builds, the cogon ridge is exposed, and dehydration risk climbs. June to October the trail closes during typhoons because the river crossings become impassable. Weekend climbs are popular, book the guide in advance from December to February.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay Before or After</h2>
<p>Mariveles and Morong have small inns and beach resorts. For a calmer post-climb base, the Las Casas Filipinas area in Bagac is a heritage-house resort that works as a reset day. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664846-Bataan_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Tarak Ridge is the overnight that earns a return visit from most climbers. The ridge campsite, the bay view, and the long river-walk approach add up to a satisfying trip. It is the right step up from Pico de Loro and the right warm-up for the bigger Bataan summits.</p>
