        'title' => 'Mt. Cinco Picos, Zambales: A Five-Peak Traverse from Subic',
        'slug' => 'mt-cinco-picos-zambales-five-peak-traverse-from-subic',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Cinco Picos in Subic, Zambales is the five-peak ridge traverse with an exposed cogon spine. Here is the trail plan, the heat strategy, and the bus loop.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Cinco Picos sits in the Zambales mountain range above Subic Bay, with five connected summits that the local Aeta community has long used as a ridge route. The trail name is literal, five peaks in a row along a cogon spine, with the highest sitting at around 920 meters. The traverse is around eight to nine hours of moving time, the climb is rated moderate to hard, and the heat on the exposed ridge is the main test.</p>
<p>Most groups do Cinco Picos as a single very long day from Manila or as an overnight with a camp on the third peak. The Aeta guides are the reliable source for trail conditions, and they run the registration table at the jump-off.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Cawag in Subic, on the Zambales coast just past the Subic Bay Freeport. Register at the Aeta tourism table, hire the local guide, and start the climb on a flat farm road that runs for the first hour. The trail crosses two small streams before the actual ascent.</p>
<h3>Peak One to Peak Three</h3>
<p>The first three peaks rise in a steady sawtooth pattern, with short descents between each summit. The cogon is shoulder-high in places and the sun is direct. Move fast through this section, the third peak has a small shaded clearing that works for a rest stop.</p>
<h3>Peak Four and Five</h3>
<p>The fourth and fifth peaks are the higher of the five, with the actual Cinco Picos summit at the fifth. The trail between four and five drops into a small saddle and climbs steeply back up. The summit view sweeps across the Zambales coast to the West Philippine Sea, with the Subic Bay opening to the south.</p>
<h3>The Optional Camp</h3>
<p>If you split the trip into two days, the standard camp is on the third peak, with a small clearing on the leeward side that holds three or four tents. Water has to be carried up, there is no spring on the ridge.</p>
<h2>The Heat Strategy</h2>
<p>The Cinco Picos ridge is one of the most sun-exposed climbs in Zambales. The cogon holds no shade, the wind drops in the middle of the day, and the heat builds fast. The fix is the same as Mt. Marami: a 4 a.m. start so you are off the high peaks by 11 a.m., or an overnight camp so the second-day climbs are early-morning starts.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Four liters of water if doing the traverse in one day</li>
<li>Electrolyte sachets, a real necessity here</li>
<li>Long-sleeve sun shirt, sunscreen, wide-brim hat</li>
<li>Trail runners with deep grip for the loose dirt descents between peaks</li>
<li>Light pack lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Headlamp for the pre-dawn start</li>
<li>Light rain layer from June to October</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the Subic descent meal</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Brgy. Cawag</h2>
<p>From Manila, ride a Victory Liner bus from Cubao bound for Iba or Sta. Cruz, and drop at the Subic Bay Freeport. From the Freeport, a jeepney or van to Brgy. Cawag is around 30 minutes. By car, take NLEX-SCTEX to the Subic exit, then the coastal Zambales road north. Total trip from Manila is around three and a half hours.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat After</h2>
<p>The Subic Bay Freeport has the usual food chains, but the longer kwento is to drive 10 minutes north of the Freeport to the Olongapo or Barretto food stretch for sisig and bulalo. The Zambales coastline north of Subic also has small carinderias along the highway with fresh tilapia from the bay.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to March are the dry, cool months and the only safe window for the full traverse. April and May the heat on the ridge is dangerous. June to October the cogon turns green and the photos soften, but the trail becomes a slippery clay slide on the descents between peaks. Weekday climbs are quietest, the trail can fill up on Saturdays from December to February.</p>
<p>Cinco Picos is the climb for trekkers who like long, exposed ridges and have a Talamitam or Marami already logged. The five summits, the saddle drops, and the wide Zambales view at the end are the kind of trip that makes climbers come back for the overnight version.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Cinco Picos Zambales: Five-Peak Traverse Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY traverse plan for Mt. Cinco Picos in Subic, Zambales. Five-peak ridge route, heat strategy, gear, transport, and the Aeta guide system.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Cinco Picos, Subic, Zambales, Five Peak Traverse, Day Hike',
