    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 11. MT. PAMULINAWEN, PASUQUIN ILOCOS NORTE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2017/02/mt-pamulinawen.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Pamulinawen, Pasuquin Ilocos Norte: A Short Climb with a Big View',
        'slug' => 'mt-pamulinawen-pasuquin-ilocos-norte-short-climb-big-view',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Pamulinawen in Pasuquin, Ilocos Norte is the short day hike with a wide coastal view. Here is the trail plan and the Laoag side trip pairing.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Pamulinawen sits in Pasuquin, Ilocos Norte, around 30 kilometers north of Laoag. The mountain is short, around 350 meters at the summit, with a one-hour climb on a wide grass ridge. The view from the top sweeps across the South China Sea on one side and the Ilocos coastal plain on the other. Pamulinawen is the kind of climb that pairs well with a Laoag overnight, an Ilocos food trip, or the longer Bangui-Pagudpud coastal loop.</p>
<p>The mountain is named after the old Ilocano love song Pamulinawen. Local guides will sometimes sing a few lines on the way up. The kwento on this mountain is more cultural than technical.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Davila in Pasuquin. Register at the barangay hall, hire a local guide, and start the climb on a flat farm path that crosses a small irrigation canal. The first 20 minutes is open farmland with a few mango trees for shade.</p>
<h3>The Grass Ridge</h3>
<p>Past the farm, the trail climbs a wide grass ridge for around 40 minutes to the summit. The grade is moderate, the path is well-worn, and the wind on the ridge is steady year-round. The grass is calf-high, not the shoulder-high cogon of Marami or Talamitam.</p>
<h3>At the Summit</h3>
<p>The peak is a wide clearing with a wooden marker and a 360-degree view. The South China Sea opens to the west, the Ilocos coastal plain stretches to the south, and on a clear morning the windmills of Bangui are faintly visible to the north. The summit holds maybe 15 trekkers comfortably.</p>
<h2>The Laoag Pairing</h2>
<p>Most groups do Pamulinawen as a half-day climb paired with a Laoag city stop. The Sinking Bell Tower, the St. William's Cathedral, and the Paoay Church are all within an hour of the jump-off. A morning climb plus an afternoon Ilocos food trip plus an evening dinner of bagnet and Ilocos longganisa is the standard one-day plan.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners or sturdy walking shoes</li>
<li>Sun hat, sunscreen, wide-brim cap</li>
<li>Two liters of water</li>
<li>Light packed snack for the summit</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the Laoag food stops</li>
<li>Light rain layer from June to October</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Pasuquin</h2>
<p>Fly to Laoag in one hour fifteen minutes from Manila with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Laoag, drive or take a jeepney north on the Manila North Road to Pasuquin, around 45 minutes. The Brgy. Davila jump-off is signposted on the highway.</p>
<h2>The Bangui-Pagudpud Combo</h2>
<p>For groups making a longer Ilocos trip, Pamulinawen fits naturally into the Bangui-Pagudpud coastal loop. Climb in the morning, drive north to the Bangui windmills for a late-afternoon stop, and stay overnight in Pagudpud for the next-day beach time. The drive from Pasuquin to Pagudpud is around 90 minutes along the coast.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to April are the dry months and the easy climbing window. The grass ridge is at its driest in February and March. May the heat builds. June to October the trail is muddy and the wind on the ridge can push hard during typhoons. The wind farm road in nearby Bangui closes during heavy rain, plan around the weather if you are combining the trip.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Laoag city has the broadest hotel selection for an Ilocos Norte base. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g303706-Laoag_Ilocos_Norte_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For the longer coast loop, Pagudpud has a row of small beach resorts along Saud and Blue Lagoon.</p>
<p>Pamulinawen is the climb to bookmark for an Ilocos road trip. The mountain is short, the view is wide, and the cultural backstory makes the walk feel different from the southern Luzon peaks. For a half-day trek that fits into a food-and-heritage Ilocos itinerary, it earns its place on the list.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Pamulinawen Pasuquin Ilocos Norte: Climb Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY half-day climb plan for Mt. Pamulinawen in Pasuquin, Ilocos Norte. Trail, summit view, Laoag pairing, Bangui-Pagudpud loop, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Pamulinawen, Pasuquin, Ilocos Norte, Laoag, Short Climb',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'laoag',
