    // 13. MT. MACULOT ROCKIES OVERNIGHT
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2007/01/mt-maculot-706.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Maculot Rockies Overnight: A Cuenca Camp Above Taal Lake',
        'slug' => 'mt-maculot-rockies-overnight-cuenca-camp-above-taal-lake',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Maculot Rockies in Cuenca, Batangas is the short climb with a wide camp above Taal Lake. Here is the trail, the camp plan, and the sunrise routine.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Maculot sits in Cuenca, Batangas, on the eastern side of Taal Lake. The mountain is most famous for the Rockies, a wide boulder field on the lower summit that gives the postcard view of the lake and the volcano. The Rockies sit at around 706 meters, lower than the actual Maculot summit but with the better view. A Saturday-night camp at the Rockies, with a sunrise the next morning, is the classic Maculot weekend plan.</p>
<p>The trail is short, around two and a half hours up, two hours down. The technical demand is low, the camp logistics are simple, and the lake view at sunrise is the photo most Filipino climbers have somewhere on their phone.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. 7 in Cuenca town. Register at the barangay hall, hire a local guide if it is your first time, and start the climb on a paved barangay road that becomes a dirt trail after 15 minutes. The first hour is a steady climb through a secondary forest.</p>
<h3>The Rockies Junction</h3>
<p>Around 90 minutes up, the trail forks. The left fork goes to the actual Maculot summit, the right fork goes to the Rockies. Most groups take the Rockies first, set up camp, then climb the summit unloaded the next morning if they want both peaks.</p>
<h3>The Rockies Campsite</h3>
<p>The Rockies is a wide boulder field with a flat clearing for tents on the leeward side. The site holds maybe 30 tents on a busy weekend. Pitch close to the boulders for wind shelter, the breeze off Taal Lake picks up at night.</p>
<h3>Sunrise at the Rockies</h3>
<p>Wake at 4:45 a.m. Walk to the boulder edge by 5:15 a.m. The sky starts to lighten over the Taal volcano, the lake fills with mist, and the sun comes up behind the Tagaytay ridge across the water. The light hits the Rockies first, then spreads across the lake. The photo takes itself.</p>
<h2>The Maculot Summit Option</h2>
<p>The actual Maculot summit is around 45 minutes from the Rockies, a steep climb through dense forest. The summit is a small clearing with limited view because of the trees. Most climbers skip it and stay at the Rockies for the lake panorama. If you want the bragging rights, the summit climb is short and the descent back to the Rockies is fast.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent and ground sheet, the boulder field has a few flat sand patches</li>
<li>Light fleece or sweater, the lake breeze cools the camp at night</li>
<li>Trail runners with grip, the rocks are slick after rain</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>Two liters of water for the climb, the camp has no spring</li>
<li>Stove and food for one dinner and one breakfast</li>
<li>Light rain layer, the lake weather changes fast</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the Cuenca descent meal</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Cuenca</h2>
<p>From Manila, ride a bus from Buendia or Cubao bound for Lipa or Lemery, and drop at the Cuenca exit on the STAR Tollway. From the exit, a tricycle to the Brgy. 7 jump-off is around 15 minutes. By car, take SLEX to STAR Tollway, exit at Cuenca, and follow the signs. Total trip from Manila is around two hours.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat After</h2>
<p>Cuenca and Lipa have lomi shops along the highway, the Batangas comfort food after a climb. Order a steaming bowl of lomi with kikiam, liver, and pork, and the climb fatigue dissolves. The Lipa coffee scene is the longer-detour option, with cafes serving Barako coffee along Sleep Lounge Avenue and the M. Marella Hotel strip.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to April are the dry, cool months and the safest for the Rockies camp. The lake view is clearest in February and March. May the heat builds even at the boulder field. June to October the climb is muddy but the post-rain mornings give the cleanest lake reflections. Weekend climbs are popular, the Rockies can carry 100 tents on a Saturday in February.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Lipa and Tagaytay are the easy overnight bases for the area. The Tagaytay side has the broader hotel selection. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g676539-Tagaytay_Cavite_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Maculot Rockies is the camp climb that earns its place on most Filipino mountaineering bucket lists. The lake view at sunrise is the kind of moment that pays back the boulder-side tent setup and the early wake. For an overnight that fits in a weekend, this is one of the easiest entries.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Maculot Rockies Overnight: Cuenca Camp Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY overnight plan for the Mt. Maculot Rockies in Cuenca, Batangas. Camp notes, sunrise view of Taal Lake, transport, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Maculot, Rockies, Cuenca, Batangas, Overnight Camp, Taal Lake',
