    // 14. CAVINTI UNDERGROUND RIVER AND PAGSANJAN GORGE KAYAK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/cavinti-underground-river-laguna/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cavinti Underground River and the Pagsanjan Gorge: A Calm Laguna Day',
        'slug' => 'cavinti-underground-river-pagsanjan-gorge-calm-laguna-day',
        'excerpt' => 'The Cavinti Underground River and the upper Pagsanjan gorge make a slow Laguna day trip. Here is the trail, the cave swim, and the kayak option above the falls.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Cavinti Underground River and Cave Complex sits above the Pagsanjan Falls, on the Cavinti side of the Magdapio River. Most travelers know Pagsanjan for the famous shooting-the-rapids banca ride from below the falls; far fewer know that the cave system, the upper river, and the gorge above the falls are a quieter, longer day trip that pairs better with a slow weekend. Tara, here is the kwento for the Cavinti side of Pagsanjan.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a morning trek into the cave complex, an afternoon kayak above the falls, and a late-afternoon stop at one of the Cavinti viewpoints. Total moving day is around eight hours.</p>
<h2>The Cave Complex</h2>
<p>The Cavinti Underground River runs through a karst limestone system inside the Cavinti tourism area. The cave entrance is a 20-minute walk from the registration office, with a gentle descent into a wide opening. Guides hand out headlamps and gloves; the rocks are sharp and the water is cool.</p>
<h3>Inside the Cave</h3>
<p>The river runs through three chambers, each with a different ceiling height. The first chamber has standing room with stalactites overhead. The second chamber narrows, you walk waist-deep through the water for around 20 meters. The third chamber opens into a wide pool, around chest-deep, with a small waterfall feeding it from above. The cave swim is the highlight; the cold pool, the carbide light on the ceiling, and the silence are the kind of stop that makes the trip worth the long Laguna drive.</p>
<h3>What to Wear in the Cave</h3>
<p>Wear aqua shoes or trail runners that drain. Wear a quick-dry top and shorts. Bring a dry bag for the phone and the wallet, the water gets up to chest height. Bring a small towel and a change of clothes for the trail back out.</p>
<h2>The Pagsanjan Gorge Kayak</h2>
<p>Above the Pagsanjan Falls, on the Cavinti side, there is a calm stretch of the Magdapio River that is suitable for a tandem kayak or a small inflatable. The local Cavinti tourism office rents the kayaks and assigns a paddle guide. The route paddles upstream from the gorge entrance, around an hour up, then drifts back down. The gorge walls rise on both sides, around 80 meters tall, and the canyon stays cool even at midday.</p>
<h3>The Devil's Cave</h3>
<p>Halfway up the kayak route, the guide will point to a small cave entrance on the canyon wall called Devil's Cave by the locals. The cave is shallow, you can paddle into it for a few meters. The water inside is dark and the temperature drops noticeably.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Aqua shoes or trail runners that drain</li>
<li>Quick-dry shirt and shorts</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>Headlamp, the cave guides have their own but a spare helps</li>
<li>Light packed lunch, the tourism area has a small canteen</li>
<li>Sunscreen for the kayak section above the gorge</li>
<li>Cash for registration, cave guide, kayak rental, and the descent merienda</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Cavinti</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a JAC Liner or DLTB bus from Buendia bound for Sta. Cruz, Laguna, and drop at the Sta. Cruz terminal. From there, a jeepney or tricycle to Cavinti town is around 40 minutes. By car, take SLEX to the Calamba exit, then the highway south through Pagsanjan and up the Cavinti road. Total trip from Manila is around three and a half hours.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the safer months. The cave river runs lower and the kayak gorge is calmer. June to October the cave can close after heavy rain because the chambers flood, the local tourism office holds the daily call. The dry months also give the cleanest cave photos because the water is clearer.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Lake Lumot and Cavinti area has farm stays and a few small lodges. Pagsanjan town has more conventional inns. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729454-Laguna_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>The Cavinti side of Pagsanjan is the quieter side. The cave swim, the gorge kayak, and the canyon view above the famous falls are the kind of day that rewards a slower itinerary. For travelers who already did the Magdapio shooting-the-rapids banca, this is the next-level Pagsanjan visit.</p>
