    // 17. ANILAO MACRO DIVING BY SEASON
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/anilao-mabini-batangas-diving/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Anilao Macro Diving by Season: A Calm Read for the Year Around',
        'slug' => 'anilao-macro-diving-by-season-calm-read-year-around',
        'excerpt' => 'Anilao in Mabini, Batangas is the macro diving capital of the Philippines. Here is the season-by-season read for the critters, the visibility, and the trip plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Anilao in Mabini, Batangas is the macro diving capital of the Philippines and one of the better critter destinations in the world. The bay sits at the mouth of the Verde Island Passage, which carries some of the highest marine biodiversity counts on the planet. Most divers know Anilao for the nudibranchs, the frogfish, and the rare octopus species, but the actual catalog of what you can see changes month by month. This is the season-by-season read for divers planning the year.</p>
<p>The bay has more than 40 named sites along a single coastal road, with most dive operations clustered around Brgy. Anilao Proper, San Teodoro, and Bagalangit. The standard dive day is three boat dives plus an optional night dive.</p>
<h2>November to February: Cooler Water, Sharper Macro</h2>
<p>The cool months bring the water temperature down to 25 to 26 degrees Celsius and the visibility up to around 20 meters. Macro photographers love this window because the sea slugs and nudibranchs come out in bigger numbers, and the muck sites at Secret Bay and Twin Rocks fill with new critters every week. The northeast monsoon brings cooler air and the boat rides feel breezy; pack a windbreaker for the surface intervals.</p>
<h3>What to Watch For</h3>
<p>Pygmy seahorses on the seafans, ghost pipefish in the rubble, and the regular cast of frogfish, blue-ringed octopus, and harlequin shrimp. Night dives in this window are quiet but rewarding.</p>
<h2>March to May: Warmer Water, Peak Visibility</h2>
<p>The warmer months push the water to 27 to 29 degrees Celsius and the visibility to 25 meters on the best days. The bay turns into the kind of conditions divers travel for. This is the peak season for the international photo workshops that run out of Anilao.</p>
<h3>What to Watch For</h3>
<p>Mandarinfish at the standard dusk sites (Secret Bay, Mainit Point) when the males come out to court. Frogfish in colors that range from yellow to red to black. Blackwater dives off the coast pull in larval squid, paper nautilus, and pelagic juveniles that ride the currents at night.</p>
<h2>June to October: Habagat Season, Calmer Crowds</h2>
<p>The southwest monsoon brings rain and the wind shifts from the bay side. The crowds drop, the dive operations stay open, and the bay is sheltered enough that the typhoons usually do not close the boat trips. Visibility drops slightly to 12 to 18 meters, and the water temperature stays at 27 to 28 degrees Celsius.</p>
<h3>What to Watch For</h3>
<p>This window is the wild-card season. New critter sightings happen because fewer divers are on the sites. The flamboyant cuttlefish, the wonderpus, and the mimic octopus all turn up on a regular basis at Mainit and Secret Bay.</p>
<h2>The Trip Plan</h2>
<p>The standard Anilao dive weekend is three days, two nights. Drive down on Friday afternoon, three dives on Saturday and Sunday morning, drive back Sunday afternoon. For divers serious about photography, a four-day or five-day stay is the better plan; the bay has too many sites for a single weekend to cover.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A 3mm wetsuit, or a 5mm if you chill easily</li>
<li>Macro lens setup for the camera, the bay is wasted with a wide-angle</li>
<li>Underwater torch, even for day dives the critters hide in shade</li>
<li>Surface interval clothes, the boats are open and breezy</li>
<li>Sunscreen reef-safe, the boat rides are sun-exposed</li>
<li>Reusable water bottle, dehydration is a real risk between dives</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Anilao</h2>
<p>From Manila, the drive is around two and a half hours down SLEX, STAR Tollway, and the Batangas coastal road through Bauan and Mabini. There is no direct public bus to Anilao Proper; the closest stop is Batangas City, then a tricycle or arranged dive-operator van to the resort area. Most dive shops include the airport or Manila transfer in the dive package.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Anilao coast has dive resorts strung along the road from Brgy. Anilao Proper to Bagalangit, with most rooms tied to a dive operation. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7287316-Mabini_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Anilao is the diving destination that earns repeat trips. The macro catalog, the season-by-season changes, and the close-to-Manila drive add up to a bay that most Filipino divers visit every year. For the macro photographer, this is one of the must-book destinations of Asia.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Anilao Macro Diving by Season: Year Around Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY season-by-season read for Anilao macro diving in Mabini, Batangas. Critter timing, visibility, trip plan, gear, and transport from Manila.',
        'tags' => 'Anilao, Mabini, Batangas, Macro Diving, Nudibranch, Frogfish',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'anilao-mabini',
