    // 18. ANILAO BLACKWATER NIGHT DIVING
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2019/03/anilao-blackwater-diving.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Anilao Blackwater Night Diving: A Calm Read on Open-Sea Drifts',
        'slug' => 'anilao-blackwater-night-diving-open-sea-drifts-read',
        'excerpt' => 'Blackwater diving off Anilao is open-ocean night drift diving for larval marine life. Here is the calm read on the routine, the critters, and the safety setup.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Blackwater diving is the night-dive practice of dropping into open ocean, away from the reef, and drifting with the current to photograph larval marine life that rises from the deep at night. Anilao is one of the most reliable blackwater destinations in the world. The Verde Island Passage, the deep channel between Batangas and Mindoro, brings up pelagic species that you cannot see anywhere else on a normal reef dive.</p>
<p>This is the calm read on what blackwater diving looks like in Anilao, what gear you need, and what to expect on the boat. The dive is not for beginners; the prerequisite is solid buoyancy, comfort in the dark, and at least 50 logged dives.</p>
<h2>The Setup</h2>
<p>The blackwater rig is a line dropped from the boat with lights at five-meter intervals down to around 25 meters. The lights attract the larval critters that rise from the depths after sunset. Divers descend along the line, hover at 15 to 20 meters in the open water, and watch the column of light for whatever drifts past.</p>
<h3>The Boat Setup</h3>
<p>The boat anchors over a 200 to 600-meter deep section of the passage. The rig drops from the side of the boat, with the lights tested at the surface first. Divers gear up on deck, do a backward roll into the dark water, and descend slowly along the line.</p>
<h3>The Dive Itself</h3>
<p>The dive is a hover, not a swim. You stay near the line, watch the lights, and shoot the critters that drift through. The current pushes the lines and the divers along, so the dive is technically a drift. The boat follows the light rig at the surface.</p>
<h2>What You See</h2>
<p>Larval squid, paper nautilus, pelagic juveniles of common reef fish, larval jellyfish, larval crustaceans, and on the best nights, an actual juvenile cephalopod or a paper-thin fish that has no name yet. The catalog rotates with the moon phase and the season. Diving on the new moon gives the best critter counts because the deep water is darker.</p>
<h3>The Photography</h3>
<p>The standard rig is a macro lens with twin strobes and a focus light. The critters are small, around 1 to 3 centimeters, and the photo demands sharp focus and patient shooting. Most divers on the boat are photographers; the practice attracts that crowd.</p>
<h2>The Safety Setup</h2>
<p>Blackwater requires a stable comfort with depth and the dark. The line is the only visual reference; if you lose the line, you drift in open water. The dive guides stay near the divers, count heads every five minutes, and the boat is always within sight of the rig. The standard dive time is 60 minutes and the standard depth is 15 to 20 meters with a safety stop at five meters.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A 5mm wetsuit, the water at depth feels cooler at night</li>
<li>A focus light and a spare</li>
<li>A signaling light or marker for safety</li>
<li>Macro setup with twin strobes for the photo work</li>
<li>A surface marker buoy and a reel</li>
<li>Dive computer with a backup</li>
<li>A wide hood to keep the head warm during the long hover</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Trip Plan</h2>
<p>Most divers book blackwater as an add-on to a standard Anilao trip. The boat leaves the resort around 7 p.m., the dive starts at 8 p.m., and the boat returns by 10 p.m. Some operators run the boat for two nights in a row; book ahead because the slots fill in the new-moon weeks. The cost is higher than a regular night dive because the boat-and-rig setup is more involved.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The peak season for blackwater in Anilao is March to May, the same period as the macro peak. The water is warm, the visibility is high, and the larval critters are at their most abundant. November to February is the colder window with quieter critter counts but still worth the night drop. June to October the trips run weather-permitting; the habagat winds can cancel the boat on rough nights.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Anilao dive resorts that run blackwater are the ones to book with directly. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7287316-Mabini_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Book the resort and the dive operator together; the operators take only their own resort guests on the blackwater boat for safety reasons.</p>
<p>Blackwater is the dive that turns the lights off on everything you thought you knew about reef diving. The drift, the dark, and the larval cast change what you look for in the water. For divers ready to step beyond the reef, Anilao is the calm starting point for the practice.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Anilao Blackwater Night Diving: Open-Sea Drift Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY read on blackwater night diving off Anilao, Mabini Batangas. Open-ocean drift setup, larval critters, gear, season timing, and the boat routine.',
        'tags' => 'Anilao, Blackwater Diving, Night Dive, Mabini, Verde Passage',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'anilao-mabini',
