    // 19. APO REEF LIVE-ABOARD
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2014/06/apo-reef-natural-park-mindoro.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Apo Reef Live-aboard from Sablayan, Mindoro: A Three-Day Dive Trip',
        'slug' => 'apo-reef-live-aboard-sablayan-mindoro-three-day-dive-trip',
        'excerpt' => 'Apo Reef in Occidental Mindoro is the second-largest contiguous reef in the world. Here is the live-aboard plan from Sablayan and the dive site notes.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Apo Reef sits in the Mindoro Strait, 33 kilometers west of Sablayan in Occidental Mindoro. The reef is the second-largest contiguous coral reef system in the world, after the Great Barrier Reef. It is uninhabited, protected as a marine national park, and reachable only by boat from Sablayan town. The standard trip is a two-night, three-day live-aboard with around 10 to 12 dives across the reef walls and the surrounding atolls.</p>
<p>This is the dive trip that Manila divers save up for a long weekend; the boat ride is around three hours each way and the dive sites are the kind that earn a return trip. Tara, here is the kwento of the live-aboard plan.</p>
<h2>The Boat Setup</h2>
<p>The Sablayan tourism office and the local operators run the trip boats, which are converted bancas with sleeping platforms above the dive deck. The boats hold around 10 to 16 divers plus the crew. Sleeping is on padded mats under a tarp roof; the trip is rustic, not yacht-class.</p>
<h3>The Dive Day</h3>
<p>The standard day is four dives, two morning and two afternoon, with surface intervals on the boat. Lunch and dinner are cooked on board by the crew, simple Filipino dishes with rice, vegetables, and fish or chicken. The boat anchors near the dive sites overnight.</p>
<h2>The Dive Sites</h2>
<p>Apo Reef has more than 20 named dive sites. The standout sites that the live-aboard rotation covers in three days are below.</p>
<h3>Apo 29</h3>
<p>The reef wall site on the southwest edge. Drops from 5 meters to over 30 meters. Reef sharks, jacks, and turtles cruise the wall. Visibility is regularly 30 meters.</p>
<h3>Shark Ridge</h3>
<p>A long ridge running along the eastern edge. Whitetip reef sharks rest on the sand patches. The current can be strong; the dive is rated intermediate to advanced.</p>
<h3>Hunter's Rock</h3>
<p>A submerged pinnacle on the south side. The site is famous for sea snakes, with up to 20 in a single dive. The pinnacle drops to 40 meters and the wall has soft corals from 25 meters down.</p>
<h3>Apo Island Reef</h3>
<p>The reef around the small Apo Island itself, where the boat ties up overnight. The shallow side has the family-friendly snorkeling. The deep side has the wall for divers.</p>
<h2>Apo Island Itself</h2>
<p>The Apo Island in Apo Reef is not the same as the Apo Island in Negros. This one is a small, uninhabited sandy island with a lighthouse and a ranger station. Walk the beach, climb the lighthouse, and watch the sunset from the western point. The island is also a fruit bat colony; thousands of fruit bats leave the trees at dusk in a swirl that goes on for around 20 minutes.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Full dive gear, the operators rent at higher prices on board</li>
<li>A 3mm wetsuit, the water is 27 to 29 degrees</li>
<li>A surface marker buoy and a reel for the wall drifts</li>
<li>Dive computer with a backup</li>
<li>Sleeping bag liner, the boat mats are basic</li>
<li>Sunscreen, the deck is exposed</li>
<li>Light layers for the night, the wind picks up</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the camera and electronics</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Sablayan</h2>
<p>From Manila, the routes are by ferry through Batangas, by Roro through Calapan, or by domestic flight to San Jose, Mindoro. The combined trip takes around 8 to 12 hours total. Fly to San Jose with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a>, then drive north to Sablayan, around two hours.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The diving season is March to June, the dry hot months, when the visibility is at its highest and the water is calm. October to February the visibility holds but the wind picks up, the boat rides get rougher. July to September the trips can cancel due to typhoons; the operators hold the daily call. The peak booking weeks are April and May.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay Before and After</h2>
<p>Sablayan town has small inns and a few beach resorts on the bay. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895126-Occidental_Mindoro_Province_Mimaropa_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Book a Sablayan room for the night before the boat leaves and the night after the boat returns.</p>
<p>Apo Reef is the dive trip that earns its place on a Filipino diver's bucket list. The wall dives, the shark ridge, the snake pinnacle, and the fruit bat island add up to a three-day experience that Tubbataha is the only other comparable destination for in the country. Plan around the season, book the live-aboard early, and the trip rewards every hour of the long boat ride.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Apo Reef Live-aboard from Sablayan Mindoro: Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY live-aboard plan for Apo Reef in Sablayan, Occidental Mindoro. Boat setup, dive site notes, fruit bat island, transport, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Apo Reef, Sablayan, Mindoro, Live-aboard, Diving, Marine Park',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'puerto-galera',
