    // 21. VERDE ISLAND PASSAGE DRIFT DIVE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/verde-island-passage-diving/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Verde Island Passage Drift Dive: A Calm Read on Open Currents',
        'slug' => 'verde-island-passage-drift-dive-open-currents-calm-read',
        'excerpt' => 'The Verde Island Passage holds the highest marine biodiversity on the planet. Here is the drift dive read from Batangas, the boat plan, and the season notes.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Verde Island Passage runs between the southern coast of Batangas and the northern coast of Mindoro. The channel is one of the world's most biodiverse marine zones, with the highest fish-species count per square kilometer measured anywhere on the planet. The Verde Island in the middle of the passage is the dive destination, with two drop-offs called The Pinnacles and The Wall that pull serious divers from across the world. The current is strong enough that the dives are drift dives; you ride the flow along the wall, not against it.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a day trip from Anilao or Batangas City, with two dives at Verde Island and a surface interval on the island itself. Tara, here is the kwento for the trip.</p>
<h2>The Boat to Verde Island</h2>
<p>The boat leaves from Anilao or Batangas City and crosses the passage to Verde Island in around 45 minutes. The crossing can be choppy when the wind picks up; pack a windbreaker. Most dive operators run the trip on regular weekends with a minimum of four divers.</p>
<h3>Verde Island Itself</h3>
<p>The island is small, around two kilometers across, with a single barangay on the protected south side. The surface interval is on the beach, with a small carinderia serving lunch. The island has no dive shops; everything comes from the boat.</p>
<h2>The Dive Sites</h2>
<h3>The Pinnacles</h3>
<p>Three submerged pinnacles rising from 40 meters to within five meters of the surface. The current splits around the pinnacles, the soft corals on the southern face are the densest in the country, and the schools of jacks and trevallies cruise the deeper sections. The drift is moderate; the dive guide leads the group around each pinnacle and signals when to ascend.</p>
<h3>The Drop-Off</h3>
<p>A vertical wall on the north side of the island, dropping from five meters to over 60 meters. The wall has hard corals on the upper section and soft corals from 20 meters down. The current here can be strong; the dive is rated advanced and is typically done after the Pinnacles dive on the same day.</p>
<h2>The Drift Dive Technique</h2>
<p>The Verde dives are not bottom-time dives. The boat drops the divers up-current of the site, the divers descend along the line, ride the drift across the wall or the pinnacles, and signal the boat with a surface marker buoy at the end. The boat follows the bubbles and picks up the divers wherever they surface.</p>
<h3>The Surface Marker Buoy</h3>
<p>Every diver carries a deployed SMB on the ascent. The boat captain watches for the orange buoy and steers to it. The SMB is not optional; the current can carry a diver 500 meters along the surface before the boat reaches them.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A 3mm wetsuit, the water is 26 to 29 degrees</li>
<li>Dive computer with a backup</li>
<li>A surface marker buoy and a reel</li>
<li>A whistle and a signaling mirror</li>
<li>Wide-angle lens, the wall photos are scenic</li>
<li>Sun-protective clothes for the boat ride</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the Verde Island stop</li>
<li>A dry bag for the wallet and phone</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to the Anilao Boat</h2>
<p>From Manila, the drive to Anilao is around two and a half hours down SLEX, STAR Tollway, and the Batangas coastal road. Most dive operators in Anilao run the Verde Island day trip on their regular schedule. Book the dive directly with the operator; the boats fill on weekends from March to May.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The Verde Island drift season is March to May, the peak Anilao season, when the visibility is highest and the current is most predictable. November to February the visibility is good but the wind shifts and the boat ride is rougher. June to October the trip cancels frequently due to weather; the operators hold the daily call. The passage has its own weather pattern because of the channel currents.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Anilao dive resorts that run the Verde trip include the dive in their dive packages. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7287316-Mabini_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The Verde Island trip is typically a day trip from Anilao, not an overnight at Verde itself.</p>
<p>The Verde Island Passage is the kind of dive that earns its scientific reputation. The fish counts, the soft corals on the pinnacles, and the wall current make for a day of diving that most Anilao regulars build into their dive trip every season. For divers who already know the bay sites, this is the next stop in the loop.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Verde Island Passage Drift Dive: Batangas Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY plan for the Verde Island Passage drift dive from Anilao, Batangas. Pinnacle and wall sites, current notes, gear, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Verde Island Passage, Drift Diving, Batangas, Anilao',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'batangas-city',
    ],

