    // 22. APO ISLAND FREEDIVING DAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/apo-island-negros-freediving/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Apo Island Freediving Day: A Calm Read from Dauin, Negros',
        'slug' => 'apo-island-freediving-day-calm-read-from-dauin-negros',
        'excerpt' => 'Apo Island off Dauin, Negros Oriental is the freediving capital of the Visayas. Here is the calm read on the boat trip, the reef, and the turtle stops.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Apo Island sits off the coast of Dauin in Negros Oriental, around 30 minutes by bangka from the mainland. The island is a marine protected area that has been managed by the local community since the 1980s, with a no-take zone, a clear reef, and a sea turtle population that grazes on the shallow seagrass beds. Apo is the freediving destination of choice in the Visayas because the water is shallow enough for breath-hold dives, the visibility is regularly 25 meters, and the turtles are reliable enough to feel like a guaranteed encounter.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a day trip from Dumaguete or Dauin, with three or four reef stops on the bangka and a swimming break on the small Apo Island beach. Tara, here is the kwento by section.</p>
<h2>The Boat Trip</h2>
<p>The bangka leaves from either Malatapay Beach in Zamboanguita, the standard port, or from any of the Dauin resorts that have their own boats. The crossing takes 30 to 45 minutes. The bangka anchors at the mooring lines at each reef site, drops the divers into the water, and waits for the surface interval.</p>
<h3>The Reef Sites</h3>
<p>Apo has more than 10 named freedive and snorkel sites. The standout rotations are below.</p>
<h3>Coconut Point</h3>
<p>A reef wall on the western edge, dropping from five meters to over 30 meters. The current is moderate. The wall has hard corals on the upper section, soft corals lower, and resident schools of anthias and sergeant fish. The freedive depth here is 10 to 15 meters for the recreational diver, deeper for the trained breath-hold athlete.</p>
<h3>Marine Sanctuary</h3>
<p>The community no-take zone on the south side of the island. The reef is in the best condition here. Turtles graze on the seagrass beds at five to seven meters; you can hover above them on a single breath. The site is also the standard photo spot.</p>
<h3>Cogon Point</h3>
<p>A reef slope on the eastern side. Lighter current, easier dive, suitable for newer freedivers. The depth is shallow enough that the underwater photographer can work without going deep.</p>
<h2>The Turtle Encounter</h2>
<p>The Apo turtles are habituated to swimmers but they are wild. Stay above them, do not touch, do not chase. The local dive guides will signal when a turtle is in sight and where to position the group. The turtle population includes both green and hawksbill turtles; the green ones are the larger and more common.</p>
<h2>The Apo Island Beach Stop</h2>
<p>Between dives, the boat ties up at the small beach on the south side. The beach has a single carinderia with halo-halo, grilled fish, and rice. Walk the short trail to the lighthouse on the high point for a view of the channel. The whole island is walkable in 90 minutes.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Long fins for the freedive sites</li>
<li>A low-volume mask and a snorkel</li>
<li>A wetsuit, 2mm or 3mm depending on cold tolerance</li>
<li>A surface marker buoy and a freedive line if doing deep recreational dives</li>
<li>Sunscreen reef-safe, the surface intervals are sun-exposed</li>
<li>A dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>Cash for the marine sanctuary fee, the guide tip, and the lunch on the island</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Dauin</h2>
<p>Fly to Dumaguete with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Dumaguete airport, a tricycle or van to Dauin is around 30 minutes south along the coastal highway. Most Dauin resorts include the airport transfer in the package.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to June are the dry, calm months when the visibility is highest and the current is mildest. November to February the visibility is still good but the wind on the surface picks up; the bangka ride feels rougher. July to October the typhoons can cancel the boat for a day, but the dive sites stay clear between storms. Peak freediver season is April and May.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Dauin has a strip of dive and freedive resorts along the coastal road. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7220796-Dauin_Negros_Oriental_Negros_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Many Dauin resorts run their own boats to Apo and bundle the trip with the dive package.</p>
<p>Apo Island is the kind of dive day that turns first-time freedivers into regulars. The shallow turtles, the clear water, and the slow island lunch are the kind of trip that pays back the long Dumaguete drive. For the freediver looking for a calm, scenic day, this is one of the must-book destinations in the Visayas.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Apo Island Freediving Day from Dauin Negros: Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY freediving day plan for Apo Island off Dauin, Negros Oriental. Reef sites, turtle encounters, gear, transport from Dumaguete, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Apo Island, Dauin, Negros Oriental, Freediving, Turtles',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'dauin',
    ],

