    // 23. LA UNION SHOULDER SEASON SURF
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thetraveljunkie.org/la-union-surf-shoulder-season/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Travel Junkie',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'La Union Shoulder Season Surf: A Calm Read for May and September',
        'slug' => 'la-union-shoulder-season-surf-calm-read-may-september',
        'excerpt' => 'La Union surf is famous in the cool months but the shoulder season has its own kwento. Here is the calm read for May and September trips to San Juan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>La Union surf is famous for the cool-season months from October to March, when the swell is biggest, the surf strip is full, and the waves at Urbiztondo regularly reach two meters on a clean morning. What gets less press is the shoulder season, the four to six weeks in May and September that bracket the peak. The waves are smaller, the surf-school crowd is thinner, and the actual surfing window is sometimes better for the intermediate to advanced rider who wants more solo time on the lineup. This is the calm read for the shoulder-season trip.</p>
<p>The peak season is the right answer for first-time surfers and for the social scene; the shoulder is the right answer for serious surfing, slower days at the beach, and rooms that are easier to book.</p>
<h2>The Surf Conditions in May</h2>
<p>May is the tail end of the cool-season swell. The waves are smaller than February, around 0.5 to 1.5 meters on a clean morning. The water is warm, around 28 degrees, and the wind is light to moderate from the northeast. The surf works best in the early morning before the wind builds.</p>
<h3>What to Expect at Urbiztondo</h3>
<p>The Urbiztondo break is the main reef-and-sand point on the surf strip. In May, the break is smaller and friendlier than peak season. The surf-school groups are still there in the morning, but the lineup spreads out by 10 a.m. Solo riders get more space.</p>
<h2>The Surf Conditions in September</h2>
<p>September is the start of the cool-season swell return. The first real swells of the season come through in the last week of August or the first week of September. The waves build through the month from 0.5 meters early to 1.5 meters by the end. The water is still warm, the wind is shifting from the southwest to the northeast.</p>
<h3>The Habagat Mornings</h3>
<p>Early September mornings can still have the habagat onshore wind. The trick is to be at the lineup by 6 a.m. before the wind picks up, then off the water by 9 a.m. when the surface chops up. By the third week of the month, the wind shifts and the surface is cleaner all day.</p>
<h2>The Surf School Question</h2>
<p>The surf schools on Urbiztondo run year-round. In the shoulder season they are easier to book and the instructor-to-student ratio is better. For first-timers, the smaller waves of May make for the easier learning curve. The two-hour beginner lesson is the standard package.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A rash guard, the sun off the water is strong</li>
<li>A board short or a long bikini suit, the surf-school boards are foamies</li>
<li>Surf wax for the cooler-water version, the warmer wax slides in summer water</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen</li>
<li>A spare set of clothes for the post-surf beach lunch</li>
<li>Light tropical layers for the evening, the breeze cools the strip</li>
<li>Cash for the surf-school lesson, the board rental, and the beach-side dining</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Trip Plan</h2>
<p>The standard shoulder-season weekend is three days, two nights. Drive up Friday afternoon, surf Saturday and Sunday mornings, return Sunday evening. For surf-only travelers, the Saturday morning is the best slot; the Sunday morning has more weekend day-trippers. A four-day stay over a long weekend gives you four surfing mornings, which is the kind of session count that actually improves the riding.</p>
<h2>Getting to San Juan</h2>
<p>Buses from Cubao or Pasay leave every hour. <a href="https://www.partas.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Partas</a> and <a href="https://www.victoryliner.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Victory Liner</a> are the main operators. Overnight trip is 6 to 7 hours; daytime with TPLEX is 5 to 5.5 hours if traffic flows. If you drive, TPLEX exit at Rosario then Manila North Road up to San Juan.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Urbiztondo surf strip has a row of beach-front rooms and small hostels. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3517488-San_Juan_La_Union_Province_Ilocos_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For quieter rooms, the San Fernando city side is 20 minutes south of the surf strip.</p>
<p>La Union shoulder season is the calm version of the surf-trip plan. The smaller waves, the thinner crowds, and the easier room booking make for a slower weekend that the cool-season visitor often misses. For the intermediate surfer or the first-time learner who wants smaller waves and more space, May and September are the right months.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'La Union Shoulder Season Surf: May and September Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY surf plan for La Union in May and September, the shoulder season. Smaller waves, thinner crowds, surf-school tips, transport, and best mornings.',
        'tags' => 'La Union, San Juan, Surf, Shoulder Season, Urbiztondo',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'san-juan-la-union',
    ],

