    // 24. BALER SHOULDER SEASON SURF WEEKEND
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thetraveljunkie.org/baler-surf-weekend/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Travel Junkie',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Baler Shoulder Season Surf: A Slow Two-Day Plan from Manila',
        'slug' => 'baler-shoulder-season-surf-slow-two-day-plan-from-manila',
        'excerpt' => 'Baler in Aurora is the east-coast surf town across the Sierra Madre. Here is the slow two-day plan, the shoulder-season swell, and the Manila bus route.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Baler is the surf town on the east coast of Luzon, in the province of Aurora, around six hours from Manila by bus. The town sits at the base of the Sierra Madre, with the long, sandy crescent of Sabang Beach as the main surf break and the smaller reef breaks at Cobra and Charlie's on the south end. Baler was the location of the original Filipino surf scene, the place where the sport entered the country in the 1980s.</p>
<p>Baler's main surf season is the habagat months from June to October, when the southwest swell pushes onto the east coast. The shoulder season in November and May has smaller waves, calmer water, and fewer surf schools on the beach. Tara, here is the slow two-day plan for the shoulder-season weekend.</p>
<h2>Day One: Arrival and the Beach</h2>
<p>The bus from Manila takes the long route through Cabanatuan and the Bongabon-Baler road, which crosses the Sierra Madre on a winding mountain pass. The drive itself is part of the trip; the road climbs through dense forest, passes the Aurora Memorial Park, and drops down to the coast.</p>
<h3>The Sabang Beach Walk</h3>
<p>After checking in, walk the length of Sabang Beach. The crescent is around two kilometers long, with the surf strip clustered in the middle and the quieter ends to the north and south. The walk takes around 45 minutes one way. The beach has a row of small restaurants along the seawall, with grilled tuna and chicken inasal as the standard order.</p>
<h3>The Sunset</h3>
<p>Sunset on the east coast is back-lit; the sun sets behind the Sierra Madre at the beach, not over the water. The light hits the wave tops first, then spreads to the sand. The colors over the mountains are the kind that make most beach photographers pause.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Surf and the Side Trips</h2>
<p>The surf in the shoulder season runs around 0.5 to 1.2 meters on a clean morning. The waves are friendly for first-time learners. The surf schools cluster along the middle of Sabang. Book the lesson for the early morning before the wind builds.</p>
<h3>The Side Trips</h3>
<p>If the surf is small or the lesson is short, the Baler area has a few worthwhile stops within 30 minutes.</p>
<h3>Diguisit Falls</h3>
<p>A short waterfall five minutes north of Sabang, with a small pool at the base. Quick swim, photo stop, back on the road.</p>
<h3>Ditumabo Mother Falls</h3>
<p>A taller waterfall around 30 minutes south of Sabang in the town of San Luis. The 30-minute trek to the falls crosses a river several times. The pool at the base is wide and cold, with the cascade plunging from 50 meters above.</p>
<h3>The Balete Tree</h3>
<p>A 600-year-old balete tree in Maria Aurora, around 20 minutes from Sabang. The tree is the kind of size that earns its own visit.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A rash guard and a board short or swimsuit</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen</li>
<li>Aqua shoes for the Mother Falls trek</li>
<li>A dry bag for the phone and wallet at the falls and the beach</li>
<li>A light long-sleeve sun shirt for the bus ride and the beach</li>
<li>Cash for the surf lesson, the falls fee, and the beach-side meals</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Baler</h2>
<p>From Manila, ride a Genesis Liner bus from Cubao or the Pasay terminal direct to Baler. The trip takes around six hours and the buses leave at scheduled slots through the day. The Joybus night service is the express option with bigger seats. Book ahead on the long weekends from December to May.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The habagat months from June to October are the high surf season with the bigger waves. The shoulder season in November and May has smaller waves and calmer crowds. December to April are the cool, dry months with the smallest and friendliest waves; the best time for first-time learners. Peak booking is the weekend of the Big-Wave Surfing Cup in February.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Sabang Beach strip has a row of beach-front rooms and small inns. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g778489-Baler_Aurora_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For quieter rooms, the south end of Sabang near the Cobra reef is the slow side.</p>
<p>Baler in the shoulder season is the calm version of the surf trip. The smaller waves, the side trips, and the slow east-coast pace make for a weekend that feels longer than two days. For travelers tired of the Manila-Tagaytay loop, this is the longer drive that pays back the bus ride.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Baler Shoulder Season Surf: Slow Two-Day Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY two-day plan for Baler in shoulder season. Sabang Beach surf, Diguisit and Mother Falls, the bus route from Manila, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Baler, Aurora, Surf, Sabang Beach, Shoulder Season',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'dingalan',
    ],

