    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/real-quezon-surf/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Real Quezon Surf Weekend: The Closer East-Coast Break from Manila',
        'slug' => 'real-quezon-surf-weekend-closer-east-coast-break-manila',
        'excerpt' => 'Real in Quezon province is the closer east-coast surf break than Baler. Here is the weekend plan, the Manila drive, and the Pacific habagat swell read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Real sits on the Pacific coast of Quezon province, around three hours from Manila by car. The town is the closer alternative to Baler for east-coast surf, with a long sand beach at Brgy. Ungos and a smaller reef break at Brgy. Sabang. The waves are not as famous as Baler's, but the trip is half the drive and the surf strip is quieter. For a Manila weekender who wants east-coast water without the six-hour Aurora bus, Real is the right answer.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a Saturday-morning surf, an afternoon at the beach, a sunset, and a Sunday-morning second session before the drive home. Total weekend is around 36 hours including travel.</p>
<h2>The Surf Conditions</h2>
<p>The Real swell comes from the Pacific. The habagat months from June to October push the bigger waves, around 1 to 2 meters on a clean morning. The amihan months from November to March bring smaller waves, around 0.5 to 1.2 meters, with the wind shifting offshore in the morning.</p>
<h3>Ungos Beach</h3>
<p>The main surf strip is at Brgy. Ungos. The beach is around two kilometers long, with the surf-school cluster in the middle and the quieter ends to the north and south. The breaks are sand-bottom; first-time surfers learn here.</p>
<h3>Sabang Reef</h3>
<p>The smaller reef break is at Brgy. Sabang, a 15-minute drive south. The wave is shorter, the takeoff is sharper, and the reef means falls hurt more. This is the intermediate surfer's call.</p>
<h2>The Surf School Setup</h2>
<p>Real has fewer surf schools than La Union or Baler. The local instructors run lessons from the Ungos beach front, with foamie boards and a two-hour beginner package as the standard. Book the lesson the night before; the schools are not online-bookable, you walk up and ask.</p>
<h2>The Side Trips</h2>
<p>If the surf is small or the group has non-surfing members, the Real area has a few stops within 30 minutes.</p>
<h3>Tignoan Beach</h3>
<p>A quieter beach 15 minutes south of Ungos. The sand is darker and the water is calm; suitable for swimming when the surf is too big at Ungos.</p>
<h3>Talay Falls</h3>
<p>A waterfall in nearby General Nakar, around 30 minutes north of Real. The trek to the falls is a short 20-minute walk along a river. The pool at the base is wide and cool.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A rash guard and a board short or swimsuit</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the sun is direct on the east coast</li>
<li>Aqua shoes for the Talay Falls trek</li>
<li>A dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>Light layers for the evening, the Pacific breeze cools the strip</li>
<li>Cash for the surf lesson, the board rental, and the beach-side meals</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Real</h2>
<p>By car, take the Marcos Highway from Marikina, through Sampaloc and Tanay, up to Sampaloc and Infanta, and into Real. The drive is around three to three and a half hours from Manila. By bus, the Genesis Liner from Cubao runs daily slots to Infanta, then a tricycle to Real. The bus trip is around four hours total.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>June to October are the peak surf months with the habagat swell. November to March are the cool months with smaller waves and clearer water. April and May are the warm months with the smallest waves. Avoid the typhoon weeks, the east coast catches the typhoons first. Check the forecast two days before the trip.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Real has a row of small surf inns along the Ungos beach front. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895031-Real_Quezon_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The neighboring Infanta town also has small lodges if Real is full.</p>
<p>Real is the closer east-coast surf trip from Manila. The waves are smaller than Baler, the drive is half, and the strip is quieter. For a weekend that wants east-coast water without the long bus ride, this is the better call. Tara, the Pacific is closer than you think.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Real Quezon Surf Weekend: Closer East-Coast Break | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY surf weekend plan for Real, Quezon. Ungos Beach surf, Sabang reef, side trips to Talay Falls, transport from Manila, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Real, Quezon, Surf, East Coast, Ungos Beach',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'quezon-province',
    ],

