    // 26. CALATAGAN MANGROVE KAYAK LOOP
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thetraveljunkie.org/calatagan-mangrove-kayak/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Travel Junkie',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Calatagan Mangrove Kayak Loop: A Calm Paddle on the Batangas Coast',
        'slug' => 'calatagan-mangrove-kayak-loop-calm-paddle-batangas-coast',
        'excerpt' => 'The Calatagan mangrove park is a slow kayak loop through restored mangrove channels. Here is the route, the bird watching, and the Manila weekend plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Calatagan sits on the southwestern tip of Batangas, where the coast curves around to face the West Philippine Sea. The town has a long stretch of beaches, the Cape Santiago lighthouse, and a quiet kayak destination that fewer Manila travelers know about, the Ang Pulo mangrove park. The park is a community-managed mangrove restoration that opened a kayak loop through the planted channels. The paddle is calm, the wildlife is shy but present, and the route is suitable for first-time kayakers.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a 90-minute morning kayak, a beach lunch, and an afternoon at the Lighthouse or at Burot Beach. Total Manila weekend is two days, one night, with the Saturday spent on the water and the Sunday on the beach.</p>
<h2>The Mangrove Kayak Route</h2>
<p>The kayak setup is at the Ang Pulo barangay tourism table. Register, get a life vest and a paddle, and the local crew launches the kayak from a small wooden pier. The route loops through the mangrove channels, around the small Pulo islet, and back to the pier.</p>
<h3>The Channels</h3>
<p>The mangroves were replanted over the last 20 years by the local community. The channels are narrow, around five to eight meters wide, with the mangrove roots arching overhead in places. Paddle slow, the water is shallow and the keel of the kayak occasionally brushes a root.</p>
<h3>The Wildlife</h3>
<p>The mangroves host fiddler crabs, mudskippers, and a quiet population of egrets and herons. The mudskippers sun on the exposed roots; the crabs scuttle in the mud. Bird watchers spot the migratory waders in November to March.</p>
<h3>The Pulo Islet</h3>
<p>The route passes the Pulo islet, a small mangrove-rimmed sandbar. Pull the kayak up, walk the perimeter, and return to the channels. The whole loop takes around 90 minutes at a leisurely pace.</p>
<h2>The Beach Stops</h2>
<p>After the kayak, drive 20 minutes south to Burot Beach or 30 minutes west to Cape Santiago Lighthouse. Burot is the long, white-sand beach with light surf and snorkel-friendly water. Cape Santiago is the 19th-century brick lighthouse on a low cliff, with a small museum and a view across the strait to Lubang Island.</p>
<h3>Lunch in the Town Center</h3>
<p>Calatagan town center has carinderias along the main road for grilled bangus, sinigang, and Batangas-style adobo. The longer-detour option is the Cape Santiago side, with small beach-side restaurants that serve fresh ulang prawns and seaweed salad.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A rash guard and a board short or swimsuit</li>
<li>Aqua shoes that drain</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>Sun hat with a chin strap, the channels are open in places</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen</li>
<li>Binoculars for the bird watching</li>
<li>Light packed snack for the islet stop</li>
<li>Cash for the kayak rental, the registration, and the beach lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Calatagan</h2>
<p>From Manila, by car, take the CAVITEX-Kawit exit, then the Aguinaldo highway south through Imus, Dasmarinas, Silang, Tagaytay, and the Nasugbu highway down through Calaca and into Calatagan. Total drive is around three hours. By bus, ride a DLTB or Saulog bus from Buendia or Pasay bound for Calatagan; the bus drops in the town proper. Total bus trip is around three and a half hours.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the calm water on the kayak channels. The bird counts are highest in November to March when the migratory species pass through. June to October the channels stay open but the rain can interrupt the paddle; the local crew will hold the call. The afternoons are warmer than the mornings; pre-9 a.m. is the better launch slot.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Calatagan has a row of small beach resorts and farm stays along the coastal road. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g4140525-Calatagan_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For a one-stop weekend, stay near Cape Santiago for the lighthouse pairing.</p>
<p>The Calatagan mangrove kayak is the calm side of Batangas adventure. The slow paddle, the mangrove canopy, and the wildlife make for a morning that feels longer than the 90 minutes on the water. For a Manila weekend that wants water time without the surf or the dive depth, this is the slow alternative.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Calatagan Mangrove Kayak Loop: Batangas Paddle Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY mangrove kayak plan for Calatagan, Batangas. Channel route, bird watching, beach stops at Burot and Cape Santiago, transport, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Calatagan, Mangrove Kayak, Batangas, Ang Pulo, Slow Paddle',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'calatagan',
    ],

