    // 27. SUBIC BAY SUP AND KAYAK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/subic-bay-watersports/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Subic Bay SUP and Kayak: A Slow Read on the Bay Routes',
        'slug' => 'subic-bay-sup-and-kayak-slow-read-bay-routes',
        'excerpt' => 'Subic Bay has paddle-friendly water and a row of operators renting SUP and kayak boards. Here is the slow read on the bay routes and the Manila drive.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Subic Bay sits inside the protected Subic Bay Freeport Zone on the Zambales coast. The bay water is calm year-round because the headlands shelter the inner waters from the open Pacific. That calm makes it one of the friendliest paddle-sport bays near Manila, with two SUP and kayak rental operations along the boardwalk. The routes inside the bay run from the Boardwalk launch to the Treasure Island sandbar and back, around two to three hours at a relaxed pace.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a Saturday-morning paddle, a Boardwalk lunch, and an afternoon at one of the Subic attractions (Ocean Adventure, Zoobic, or the Treetop Adventure). Total weekend is two days, one night. Tara, here is the kwento for the bay routes.</p>
<h2>The Boardwalk Launch</h2>
<p>The main rental and launch point is the Subic Bay Boardwalk on the inner bay side. The two main operators set up their boards along the seawall every morning from 7 a.m. Register, get the life vest and the paddle, and the crew launches the SUP or the kayak from the small concrete ramp.</p>
<h3>SUP Versus Kayak</h3>
<p>The SUP is the standing paddle board, more workout, more view, more balance challenge. The kayak is the sitting boat, more relaxed, easier for first-timers, faster across the open water. Both work the same routes.</p>
<h2>The Treasure Island Route</h2>
<p>The standard route paddles from the Boardwalk to the Treasure Island sandbar, around 40 minutes one way at a calm pace. The sandbar is a small spit on the southern shore, exposed at low tide, with the bay water on three sides. Pull the board up, take photos, drift back.</p>
<h3>The All Hands Beach Route</h3>
<p>For groups with more time, the longer route paddles north to All Hands Beach, around 90 minutes one way. The beach is a calm cove with the All Hands Pavilion at the back. This route is for fitter paddlers.</p>
<h2>The Wildlife</h2>
<p>The bay water is clear enough that you can see the fish below the board. The sergeant fish, the yellow tail snappers, and the occasional puffer pass under the SUP. The bay also has a resident dolphin pod that occasionally surfaces in the inner waters; if you see them, do not chase them, they will swim closer if you keep still.</p>
<h2>The Subic Attractions</h2>
<p>If you have a full weekend, the Subic Bay Freeport has the standard attractions for a one-stop family trip.</p>
<h3>Ocean Adventure</h3>
<p>A marine park with a sea lion show, a dolphin program, and the underwater walking pool. Family-friendly. Half-day visit.</p>
<h3>Zoobic Safari</h3>
<p>A safari park with a tiger feeding tour. Children's-favorite attraction. Half-day visit.</p>
<h3>Treetop Adventure</h3>
<p>A rope-and-zip-line course in the forested hills above the Boardwalk. Around two hours for the full course.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A rash guard and a board short or swimsuit</li>
<li>Aqua shoes that drain</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>Sun hat with a chin strap</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen</li>
<li>A reusable water bottle</li>
<li>Cash for the SUP or kayak rental and the Boardwalk lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Subic</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX-SCTEX to the Subic exit, then the inner road to the Boardwalk. The drive is around two and a half hours from Quezon City. By bus, ride a Victory Liner bus from Cubao bound for Olongapo, and drop at the Subic Bay Freeport gate. Total bus trip is around three hours.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry, calm months and the easiest for the SUP paddle. The bay water is glass-calm in the early morning. June to October the bay still works but the rain can interrupt the rental; the crew will hold the call. The afternoons can have light chop when the wind picks up; the morning launch is the better slot.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Subic Bay Freeport has a row of bay-front hotels and resorts along the Boardwalk. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g676605-Subic_Bay_Freeport_Zone_Zambales_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The neighboring Olongapo and Barretto strip have more budget options.</p>
<p>Subic Bay SUP and kayak is the slow side of the Zambales weekend. The calm bay, the easy paddle, and the family-friendly attractions on land make for a weekend that suits a wider group than the surfer-only trips farther north. For a base-camp weekend with water and land options, this is one of the closer answers from Manila.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Subic Bay SUP and Kayak: Bay Routes Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY SUP and kayak plan for Subic Bay, Zambales. Boardwalk launch, Treasure Island and All Hands routes, attractions, transport, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Subic Bay, SUP, Kayak, Zambales, Boardwalk, Freeport',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'subic',
    ],

