    // 29. ALIWAGWAG FALLS 84-TIER TREK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/aliwagwag-falls-davao-oriental/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Aliwagwag Falls 84-Tier Trek: A Calm Read on the Cateel Cascade',
        'slug' => 'aliwagwag-falls-84-tier-trek-cateel-cascade-calm-read',
        'excerpt' => 'Aliwagwag Falls in Cateel, Davao Oriental is the 84-tier cascade trek through a forested gorge. Here is the calm read on the trail, the canopy, and the drive.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Aliwagwag Falls sits in Cateel, Davao Oriental, on the eastern coast of Mindanao. The falls are not a single drop but a series of 84 cascades that stair-step down a forested gorge for around 340 meters of total height. The system has been called the "stairway of angels" by locals, and it is the kind of geological feature that does not exist anywhere else in the country at this scale. The Davao Oriental tourism office has built a canopy walk, a viewing platform, and a small zipline at the lower section of the falls.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a half-day visit to the lower platform and canopy walk, with a swim at the lowest pool. The longer trek to the upper cascades is for fit trekkers with a guide and a full day to spare. Tara, here is the kwento for the visit.</p>
<h2>The Lower Falls Area</h2>
<p>The tourism office is at the main entrance, with the registration table, the parking, and the start of the canopy walk. Register, pay the small fee, and the staff direct you to the first viewing deck. The lower cascade is wide and powerful, with the water dropping into a deep blue-green pool that you can swim in.</p>
<h3>The Canopy Walk</h3>
<p>The canopy walk is a steel-frame walkway that runs along the gorge wall at around 30 meters above the river. The walk takes around 20 minutes one way. The view from the walkway opens to the cascade system, with multiple drops visible in succession. The handrails are sturdy and the walk is family-friendly.</p>
<h3>The Zipline</h3>
<p>The zipline runs from the canopy walk's far end back across the gorge to a landing platform near the entrance. The ride takes around 30 seconds. The view from the line is the kind that pays back the small fee.</p>
<h2>The Upper Cascades Trek</h2>
<p>For trekkers who want to see the higher cascades, the local guide will lead a longer trek that follows the river upstream. The trek takes around four to six hours round trip, with multiple river crossings and a few rope-assisted scrambles. Wear trail runners with grip and bring three liters of water.</p>
<h3>What You See on the Upper Trek</h3>
<p>The middle cascades are the tallest of the system, with single drops of 30 to 40 meters that the lower-trek visitor never sees. The pools at the base of each cascade are clearer because the gorge is narrower at the higher elevation. The forest canopy thickens; the bird sounds are constant.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners or hiking shoes with grip</li>
<li>Quick-dry shirt and shorts</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>Aqua shoes for the pool swim</li>
<li>Three liters of water for the upper trek, one liter for the lower visit</li>
<li>Light rain layer, the gorge holds moisture</li>
<li>Sunscreen for the canopy walk</li>
<li>Cash for the registration, canopy walk, zipline, guide tip, and the Cateel meal</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Aliwagwag</h2>
<p>Fly to Davao with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Davao city, the drive to Aliwagwag is around six to seven hours along the Davao Oriental coastal highway through Mati and Baganga. Most travelers stay overnight in Mati or Baganga to break the drive. The neighboring Cateel town has small inns near the falls entrance.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the safer trekking window for the upper cascades. The lower platform and canopy walk run year-round, weather permitting. June to October the falls are at their most powerful, with the gorge filling with mist and the photos turning dramatic. The wet season can close the upper trek; the local guide will hold the call. Avoid the typhoon weeks, the eastern Mindanao coast catches them.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Cateel and Baganga have small inns and beach-side resorts. For a longer Davao Oriental loop, the Mati town has the broader hotel selection. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g4502473-Davao_Oriental_Province_Davao_Region_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Aliwagwag is the kind of natural feature that earns the long Davao Oriental drive. The 84-cascade system, the canopy walk, and the gorge view are unique enough that few falls in the country compare. For travelers building a long Mindanao itinerary, this is one of the eastern coast highlights.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Aliwagwag Falls 84-Tier Trek: Davao Oriental Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY plan for Aliwagwag Falls in Cateel, Davao Oriental. Canopy walk, lower swim, upper cascades trek, transport from Davao, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Aliwagwag Falls, Cateel, Davao Oriental, 84-Tier Falls, Canopy Walk',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'davao-city',
    ],

