        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Casaroro Falls Trek, Valencia Negros: A Quiet Steep-Stairs Hike',
        'slug' => 'casaroro-falls-trek-valencia-negros-quiet-steep-stairs-hike',
        'excerpt' => 'Casaroro Falls in Valencia, Negros Oriental is the steep-stairs trek to a 30-meter cascade. Here is the trail, the swim, and the Dumaguete weekend pairing.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Casaroro Falls sits in Valencia, Negros Oriental, around 25 kilometers from Dumaguete. The falls drop 30 meters into a wide green pool in a narrow forested gorge. The trek down to the falls is short but steep, with a 335-step concrete stairway built into the gorge wall, then a 15-minute walk along the river to the base. The trip works as a half-day visit from Dumaguete or as the morning leg of a Twin Lakes-Casaroro combination.</p>
<p>Casaroro is one of the more accessible falls in the Visayas, but the climb back up the 335 steps is the test. Pace yourself, take the rest stops, and the pool at the bottom pays back the descent.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The trail starts at the Valencia tourism office, where you register and pay the small fee. The local guide assigns the route and walks the steps with the group. The 335 steps drop down the gorge wall in a switchback pattern; the steps are concrete but worn smooth in places.</p>
<h3>The River Walk</h3>
<p>At the bottom of the steps, the trail crosses the river on a small bamboo bridge, then follows the river upstream for 15 minutes. The river is shallow, around knee-deep in the dry months. Wear aqua shoes or shoes you can wet, the river crossings are part of the route.</p>
<h3>The Falls and the Pool</h3>
<p>The falls open at the head of the gorge. The 30-meter drop is narrow, with the water falling into a circular pool surrounded by mossy rock walls. The pool is around four meters deep at the center; locals say it is safe to swim across. The cascade kicks up a constant mist; expect to get wet just standing on the bank.</p>
<h2>The Climb Back</h2>
<p>The 335 steps up are the test of the day. The grade is steep, the steps are uneven, and the heat builds even in the morning. Pace yourself, take a rest every 75 steps or so, and drink water at the marked rest platforms. The whole climb up takes around 30 minutes for a fit hiker, 45 minutes for a casual visitor.</p>
<h2>The Twin Lakes Pairing</h2>
<p>The Twin Lakes (Balinsasayao and Danao) sit 20 minutes from the Casaroro turnoff, on the same Valencia road. For a full day, do Casaroro in the morning, drive to Twin Lakes for the afternoon, and return to Dumaguete by sunset. The Twin Lakes have a boat ride across Balinsasayao Lake and a kayak option on Danao.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners or aqua shoes that grip wet stone</li>
<li>Quick-dry shirt and shorts</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>A swim suit for the pool</li>
<li>Two liters of water for the climb back</li>
<li>Light packed snack</li>
<li>A small towel for after the swim</li>
<li>Cash for the registration, the guide tip, and the Valencia restaurant lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Casaroro</h2>
<p>Fly to Dumaguete with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Dumaguete, the trip to Casaroro is around 45 minutes by tricycle or rented motorcycle. The road climbs into Valencia, then a smaller road branches off to the falls entrance. A habal-habal (motorcycle) is the local transport from the Valencia town center.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the easier climbing window. The river crossings are shallow and the gorge is comfortable. June to October the falls run more powerfully and the photos are dramatic, but the steps and the river crossings are slipperier. The wet season can close the trail during heavy rain; the local guide will hold the call. Mornings are quieter than afternoons.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Dumaguete has the broadest hotel selection for the Negros Oriental base. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g678538-Dumaguete_Negros_Oriental_Negros_Island_Visayas-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For a quieter overnight, Valencia has small mountain lodges 20 minutes from the falls.</p>
<p>Casaroro is the falls trip that earns its place on a Dumaguete weekend. The steep steps are the test, the pool is the reward, and the cool mist of the gorge is the kind of break from the humid coast that pays back the trip. For a half-day adventure that pairs with Twin Lakes or Apo Island, this is one of the easy picks.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Casaroro Falls Trek, Valencia Negros: Day Hike Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY trek plan for Casaroro Falls in Valencia, Negros Oriental. 335-step descent, river walk, pool swim, transport from Dumaguete, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Casaroro Falls, Valencia, Negros Oriental, Dumaguete, Day Hike',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'dumaguete',
    ],

