    // 31. LAKE HOLON T'BOLI WEEKEND
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.lakwatsero.com/destination/lake-holon-tboli/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Lakwatsero',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Lake Holon, Tboli South Cotabato: A Slow Crater Lake Weekend',
        'slug' => 'lake-holon-tboli-south-cotabato-slow-crater-lake-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'Lake Holon in T\'boli, South Cotabato is the crater lake at the foot of Mt. Parker. Here is the slow weekend plan, the trek, and the Gen. Santos drive.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Lake Holon sits in the crater of Mt. Parker (Melibingoy) in T\'boli, South Cotabato. The lake is at 1,800 meters elevation, with the rim of the crater rising another 200 meters above the water. The lake is sacred to the T\'boli community, the indigenous people who live around the mountain. The community manages the access to the trail and the lake, with two routes (Salacafe and Kule) and a strict registration system. The kwento here is the lake itself, the trek, and the slow weekend among the T\'boli villages.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a Friday-night arrival at the T\'boli town, a Saturday-morning trek up to the rim, an afternoon descent to the lake, an overnight camp on the lake shore, and a Sunday-morning trek out. Total weekend is three days, two nights including the Gen. Santos travel.</p>
<h2>The Salacafe Trail</h2>
<p>The Salacafe trail is the standard route for first-time Holon trekkers. The trailhead is at Brgy. Salacafe in the T\'boli town, with the registration table and the guide assignment. The trail climbs through a coffee farm, then a grass slope, then a forested ridge to the crater rim. Total moving time is around five hours up.</p>
<h3>The Crater Rim</h3>
<p>The rim is a sharp ridge with the lake on one side and the South Cotabato lowland on the other. The view from the rim opens to the lake below, the surrounding T\'boli mountains, and on a clear day the Sarangani coast in the distance.</p>
<h3>The Descent to the Lake</h3>
<p>From the rim, the descent to the lake takes around 90 minutes on a steep trail. The path drops 200 meters in elevation through a thinning forest to the lake shore.</p>
<h2>The Lake Camp</h2>
<p>The camp is on a small flat clearing at the lake's western shore. The site has flat ground for tents, a small spring, and a designated cooking area. The lake water is cold; the T\'boli ask that visitors swim only at the marked area on the eastern shore.</p>
<h3>The Sunset on the Lake</h3>
<p>The sun sets behind the rim and the light hits the lake in soft layers. The water mirrors the sky; the photos are quiet and patient.</p>
<h3>The Night</h3>
<p>The night at the lake is silent, with only the occasional bird call and the wind across the water. Pack a warm layer; the elevation drops the temperature to 14 to 16 degrees by midnight.</p>
<h2>The Kule Trail Option</h2>
<p>The Kule trail is the alternate route. It is shorter (three hours up) but steeper. Some groups go up Salacafe and down Kule for a traverse experience. Coordinate the traverse with the T\'boli tourism office; the two trails require separate registration and guide arrangements.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent and ground sheet, the camp is at high elevation</li>
<li>Warm jacket and a wool layer for the night</li>
<li>Trail runners with deep lugs for the descent</li>
<li>Three liters of water for the climb up, the camp spring refills</li>
<li>Stove and food for one dinner and one breakfast</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>A swim suit for the marked lake swim area</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, the T\'boli community fee, and the Gen. Santos meal</li>
</ul>
<h2>The T'boli Cultural Note</h2>
<p>The lake is sacred to the T\'boli. Respect the local protocols: no loud music, no swimming outside the marked area, no littering, no rocks taken as souvenirs. The community runs the trail because they want to protect both the lake and their cultural ties to it. The guide will brief you at the registration; listen carefully.</p>
<h2>Getting to Tboli</h2>
<p>Fly to General Santos with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Gen. Santos, the drive to T\'boli town is around two and a half hours north through Polomolok and Surallah. Most travelers stay overnight in T\'boli or in nearby Lake Sebu the night before the climb.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the cool, dry months and the safer climbing window. The lake is clearest in February and March. June to October the trail becomes muddy and the lake camp is wetter. The wet season also has more lake mist, which gives dramatic photos but limits the view. Avoid the typhoon weeks. The T\'boli tourism office has a daily-cap on permits; book ahead.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>T\'boli town has small homestays. Lake Sebu, 30 minutes away, has the broader lodge selection along the lake. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895029-Lake_Sebu_South_Cotabato_Province_Soccsksargen_Region_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Lake Holon is the crater-lake weekend that earns the long Mindanao trip. The climb, the rim view, the lake camp, and the T\'boli culture make for a trip that few other Filipino destinations match. For a slow outdoor weekend with both nature and culture, this is one of the southern picks worth the flight.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Lake Holon Tboli South Cotabato: Crater Lake Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY two-night plan for Lake Holon in T\'boli, South Cotabato. Salacafe trail, crater rim view, lake camp, T\'boli culture notes, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Lake Holon, Tboli, South Cotabato, Crater Lake, Mt. Parker',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'general-santos',
    ],

