    // 32. HIDDEN VALLEY SPRINGS, CALAUAN LAGUNA
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thetraveljunkie.org/hidden-valley-springs-calauan/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Travel Junkie',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Hidden Valley Springs, Calauan Laguna: A Slow Day in the Forest Pools',
        'slug' => 'hidden-valley-springs-calauan-laguna-slow-day-forest-pools',
        'excerpt' => 'Hidden Valley Springs in Calauan, Laguna is the forest pool day-trip from Manila. Here is the slow read on the springs, the trail, and the easy weekend route.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Hidden Valley Springs sits in Calauan, Laguna, around two hours south of Manila by car. The property is built around a series of natural cold and warm springs that fill several pools set inside an old crater valley. The water comes up from the volcanic foothills of Mt. Makiling, the air is cooler than the lowland thanks to the elevation, and the forest around the springs has been replanted with native species. The kwento here is the slow day, not the adrenaline; the springs work for families, couples, and solo travelers who want a quiet pool day with a small trek.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a morning arrival, a short trek into the property, a lunch break, an afternoon at the pools, and a late-afternoon drive home. Total day is around 10 hours including the Manila travel.</p>
<h2>The Entry Trek</h2>
<p>The property's entrance is at the top of the crater rim. From the parking area, a short concrete path winds down into the valley, around 15 minutes of walking. The trail passes a few small streams and a viewing platform that opens to the pools below.</p>
<h3>The Crater Valley</h3>
<p>The valley itself is the property. The springs sit at the bottom, fed by underground volcanic warm water in one section and cool spring water in another. The temperature difference between the two main pools is around 10 degrees Celsius; the warm pool feels like a relaxed bath, the cool pool feels like a mountain stream.</p>
<h2>The Pools</h2>
<p>The property has three named pools and a small waterfall.</p>
<h3>The Warm Spring Pool</h3>
<p>The main warm pool sits near the eastern end of the valley. The water is around 32 to 35 degrees Celsius, fed by an underground spring. The pool is concrete-bottomed for hygiene, with the natural rock walls around it.</p>
<h3>The Cool Spring Pool</h3>
<p>The cool pool is across the valley from the warm one. The water is around 22 to 24 degrees, fed by mountain runoff. The pool is wider, with a small waterfall at one end.</p>
<h3>The Waterfall</h3>
<p>The valley's small waterfall drops around eight meters into a shallow pool. The water is the cool-spring type. You can stand under the falls for a natural shoulder massage; the locals call it the original spa treatment.</p>
<h2>The Trekking Side Trip</h2>
<p>If you want more than the pool day, the property has a short trail that climbs to a viewing deck above the valley. The trek takes around 30 minutes one way, with a few rope-assisted scrambles. The deck opens to a wide view of the Laguna lowland.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>A swim suit or a board short</li>
<li>A rash guard for sun protection</li>
<li>Aqua shoes that grip wet stone</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the phone and wallet</li>
<li>A small towel</li>
<li>Reef-safe sunscreen for the open pool</li>
<li>A change of clothes for the drive home</li>
<li>Cash for the entry, the lunch, and the merienda</li>
</ul>
<h2>The Day-Tour Versus Overnight Option</h2>
<p>The property runs a day-tour package and an overnight package. The day tour is the standard call for Manila weekenders; arrive at 9 a.m., leave by 4 p.m. The overnight is the slower option, with cabin-style rooms inside the valley. Book either through the property's official channels; walk-ins are not always accepted.</p>
<h2>Getting to Calauan</h2>
<p>From Manila, take SLEX to the Calamba exit, then the national highway south through Bay and into Calauan. The property is signposted from the highway. The drive is around two hours from Quezon City. By bus, the JAC Liner or DLTB from Buendia drops at the Calauan turnoff, then a tricycle to the property.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry, cool months and the best for the pool day. The air is comfortable and the trek is dry. June to October the pools still work but the rain can interrupt the visit; the property holds the daily call. The mornings are quieter than the afternoons. Weekday visits are the slowest; weekends from December to April can fill up.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The property has its own cabins for the overnight package. For a separate base, San Pablo town is 20 minutes away with small inns. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729454-Laguna_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Hidden Valley Springs is the slow side of the Laguna day trip. The forest pools, the small trek, and the cool-water swim make for a calm weekend that suits a wider group than the adrenaline routes. For Manila travelers who want a forest pool day without the long drive, this is the slow alternative to Pansol.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Hidden Valley Springs Calauan Laguna: Pool Day Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY day-trip plan for Hidden Valley Springs in Calauan, Laguna. Warm and cool spring pools, forest trek, transport from Manila, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Hidden Valley Springs, Calauan, Laguna, Forest Pools, Day Trip',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'san-pablo',
    ],

