    // 33. MT. DAGULDOL DAY HIKE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2007/06/mt-daguldol.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Daguldol Day Hike: A Beach-to-Summit Climb in San Juan Batangas',
        'slug' => 'mt-daguldol-day-hike-beach-to-summit-climb-san-juan-batangas',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Daguldol in San Juan, Batangas is the beach-to-summit climb above the Laiya coast. Here is the trail, the camp option, and the post-climb beach plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Daguldol sits in San Juan, Batangas, the same coastal town as Laiya Beach. The mountain is short, around 672 meters at the summit, with a trail that starts a few kilometers inland from the Laiya beach front. The climb takes three to four hours up, two to three hours down, on a moderate trail through a coconut grove and a secondary forest. The standout feature is the summit camp; the open clearing at the top has a view of the West Philippine Sea and the Mindoro coastline across the strait. After the climb, the Laiya beach is a 20-minute drive away, which makes the trip a rare beach-and-mountain weekend.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a Saturday-afternoon climb, a sunset on the summit, an overnight camp, and a Sunday-morning descent with the afternoon at Laiya beach. Total weekend is two days, one night. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Hugom in San Juan, around five minutes inland from the Laiya beach front. Register at the barangay tourism table, hire a local guide, and start the climb on a coconut farm path that runs flat for the first 20 minutes.</p>
<h3>The Forest Section</h3>
<p>Past the coconut grove, the trail climbs through a secondary forest for around two hours. The canopy holds the heat off and the trail is rooty but well-shaded. The bird sounds are constant. The forest opens to a small grass clearing at the halfway point, a good rest stop.</p>
<h3>The Cogon Ridge</h3>
<p>The upper third of the climb runs along a cogon ridge with the first sea views opening to the right. The grass is calf-high, the wind picks up, and the sun is direct. Move steadily through this section; the campsite is at the end of the ridge.</p>
<h3>The Summit Campsite</h3>
<p>The summit is a wide open clearing with a view of the West Philippine Sea to the southwest and the Mindoro coast across the strait. The site holds around 20 tents on a busy weekend. Pitch on the leeward side; the sea wind pushes hard at night.</p>
<h2>The Sunset and Sunrise</h2>
<p>Sunset at the summit is the standard photo. The sun drops behind the Mindoro silhouette and the light spreads across the strait. The sunrise is back-lit, with the light coming up from behind the camp, but the eastern view across the Laiya bay is the second photo of the trip.</p>
<h2>The Laiya Beach Afternoon</h2>
<p>After the Sunday-morning descent, drive 20 minutes east to Laiya Beach. The white-sand crescent at Laiya is around two kilometers long, with the resort row clustered in the middle. Swim, eat lunch at a beach-side carinderia, and start the drive home by mid-afternoon. The combination of a summit overnight and a beach Sunday is the kind of weekend that few Manila destinations offer.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent with a rain fly, the summit wind is real</li>
<li>Light fleece or sweater, the sea breeze cools the camp at night</li>
<li>Trail runners with deep lugs for the rooty forest</li>
<li>Two and a half liters of water for the climb, the camp has no spring</li>
<li>Stove and food for one dinner and one breakfast</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>A swim suit and a rash guard for the Laiya beach afternoon</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the beach-side lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to San Juan</h2>
<p>From Manila, take SLEX to the STAR Tollway, exit at Lipa, then drive south through Padre Garcia, Rosario, and into San Juan. The drive is around two and a half hours from Quezon City. By bus, ride a JAM Liner from Buendia to San Juan, then a tricycle to the Hugom jump-off.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the safer climbing window. The trail surface is firm and the summit camp is comfortable. June to October the cogon ridge becomes slick and the summit camp gets exposed to the habagat winds. The summer months (March to May) can be hot on the cogon section; start the climb in the late afternoon, not the morning. Avoid the typhoon weeks.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Laiya has the broad beach-resort row for the beach pairing. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7287321-San_Juan_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The mountain campsite is the only overnight on the climb itself.</p>
<p>Daguldol is the beach-and-mountain combo that few Filipino destinations match. The summit, the sea view, and the Laiya beach the next day make for a weekend that pays back the drive. For trekkers who want a coastal climb with a swim at the end, this is one of the closer answers from Manila.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Daguldol Day Hike: San Juan Batangas Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY climb plan for Mt. Daguldol in San Juan, Batangas. Summit camp, sea view, Laiya beach pairing, transport from Manila, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Daguldol, San Juan, Batangas, Laiya, Beach Mountain Combo',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'laiya',
    ],

