    // 34. MT. LOBO TRAIL, BATANGAS
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2008/03/mt-lobo.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Lobo Trail, Batangas: A Quiet Day Climb on the Verde Coast',
        'slug' => 'mt-lobo-trail-batangas-quiet-day-climb-verde-coast',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Lobo in Lobo, Batangas is the quiet day climb above the Malabrigo lighthouse coast. Here is the trail, the lighthouse pairing, and the slow Verde view.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Lobo sits in Lobo, Batangas, on the southeastern coast of the province where the Verde Island Passage meets the Pacific. The mountain is around 750 meters at the summit, with a trail that climbs through a banana grove, then a secondary forest, then a cogon ridge to a small open peak. The view from the summit opens to the Verde Island Passage on one side and the Lobo coast on the other, with the Malabrigo lighthouse visible to the south. Lobo is the lesser-known sibling of the more famous Batangas climbs; the trail is quieter, the locals know fewer trekkers, and the Verde view at the top is the kind of payoff that justifies the long drive.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a Saturday morning climb, an afternoon at the Malabrigo lighthouse, and a Sunday drive home. The trip works as a single overnight or as a stretched day trip if you start before dawn.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Sawang in Lobo town. Register at the barangay tourism table, hire a local guide, and start the climb on a flat farm road through a banana grove. The first 30 minutes is open farm with no shade.</p>
<h3>The Forest Belt</h3>
<p>The middle section is a secondary forest that runs for around two hours. The canopy is thick, the air is cooler, and the trail is rooty but well-marked. The forest opens to a small clearing around 90 minutes into the climb, with a view back to the Lobo coast.</p>
<h3>The Cogon Summit</h3>
<p>The last 45 minutes runs along a cogon ridge to the summit. The grass is calf-high to chest-high, the sun is direct, and the wind picks up. The summit clearing is small, around 10 trekkers fit comfortably. The view opens to the Verde Island Passage to the north, the Lobo coast to the east, and the Malabrigo Point to the south.</p>
<h2>The Malabrigo Lighthouse Pairing</h2>
<p>After the climb, drive 30 minutes south to the Malabrigo lighthouse. The 1891 brick tower sits on the southeast tip of the Lobo coast, with a small keeper's house and a wide bay view. The lighthouse is a working light; visitors can climb to the gallery for the panoramic view of the Verde Passage and the Mindoro coast across the strait. Sunset from the lighthouse is the standard descent meal.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners with grip for the rooty forest</li>
<li>Sun hat, sunscreen, and a long-sleeve sun shirt for the cogon</li>
<li>Two liters of water, no spring on the trail</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Light rain layer from June to October</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the lighthouse lunch</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Lobo</h2>
<p>From Manila, take SLEX to the STAR Tollway, exit at Batangas City, then drive east through Lipa and into Lobo. The drive is around three hours from Quezon City. By bus, ride a JAM Liner or DLTB from Buendia to Batangas City, then a jeepney bound for Lobo. The Brgy. Sawang jump-off is along the main road into the Lobo town center.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry, cool months and the easier climbing window. The cogon ridge is comfortable in the cool dry season. June to October the trail becomes muddy and the cogon section gets exposed to the wind. The summer months (March to May) bring the strongest sun on the cogon; start before dawn if climbing in summer. Avoid the typhoon weeks; the southeast coast catches them.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Lobo town has small inns near the coast. The Laiya beach row is 45 minutes north for a broader resort selection. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7287321-San_Juan_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Lobo is the quieter Batangas climb. The forest, the cogon summit, and the Malabrigo lighthouse make for a calm day that pays back the longer drive. For trekkers tired of the Nasugbu and Cuenca crowds, this is the southeastern alternative.</p>
