    // 35. MT. MAKILING NORTH TRAIL
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2007/01/mt-makiling.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Makiling North Trail: A Quiet Climb from Los Baños, Laguna',
        'slug' => 'mt-makiling-north-trail-quiet-climb-los-banos-laguna',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Makiling has two main trails; the UPLB north trail is the quieter forest climb. Here is the trail plan, the forest read, and the Los Baños hot-spring pairing.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Makiling sits between Laguna and Batangas, with the main university town of Los Baños on its northern slope. The mountain has two main climb routes: the popular Sto. Tomas trail on the southern side, and the quieter UPLB north trail on the Los Baños side. The north trail is the forested approach, with a longer route through a closed-canopy secondary forest and a steeper finish at the Makiling summit (1,090 meters). For trekkers who want a quiet, shaded climb without the crowds of the southern trail, the north route is the answer.</p>
<p>The climb takes around four hours up, three hours down, on the north trail. Most groups do the climb as a single long day from Manila, with the afternoon at the Los Baños hot springs.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at the UPLB Forestry compound in Los Baños. Register at the gate, pay the small fee, and hire a forestry-accredited guide. The trail starts at the UPLB Mudspring area, climbs past the Mudspring lookout, and enters the closed-canopy forest.</p>
<h3>The Mudspring Section</h3>
<p>The Mudspring is a sulfur-vent pool around 30 minutes into the climb. The water is muddy gray, the air smells of sulfur, and the small pool bubbles continuously. The site is a quick photo stop; do not touch the water, the temperature is around 70 degrees Celsius.</p>
<h3>The Forest Section</h3>
<p>Past the Mudspring, the trail climbs through the Makiling secondary forest for around three hours. The canopy is dense and the trail is well-shaded. The forest holds the famous Makiling biodiversity; the trees include Philippine teak, narra, and the endemic almaciga. Birds are constant; the local birdwatchers come here for the rufous coucal and the white-eared brown dove.</p>
<h3>The Summit</h3>
<p>The summit (Peak 2) is the standard turnaround for north-trail climbs. The clearing is small with limited view because of the trees. The forest is the trip, not the panorama. A separate Peak 1 (the actual highest point) sits a 20-minute walk away and has even less view.</p>
<h2>The Los Baños Hot Springs</h2>
<p>After the climb, the Los Baños hot-spring strip is a 20-minute drive from the UPLB gate. The local pools are fed by underground volcanic water with a temperature of around 38 to 42 degrees Celsius. The standard descent meal is a hot-spring soak followed by buko pie at the Lety's Buko Pie shop along the highway. The soak after a Makiling climb is the kind of recovery that turns a long day into a manageable evening.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners with deep lugs for the rooty forest</li>
<li>Long-sleeve sun shirt, the forest has limatik (forest leeches)</li>
<li>Anti-leech spray or salt for the limatik</li>
<li>Three liters of water, no spring on the trail</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Light rain layer, the forest holds moisture year-round</li>
<li>A change of dry clothes for the hot spring</li>
<li>Cash for the UPLB registration, the guide, and the hot-spring entry</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Los Baños</h2>
<p>From Manila, take SLEX to the Calamba exit, then the national highway south through Calamba and into Los Baños. The UPLB campus is on the western edge of the town. The drive is around 90 minutes from Quezon City. By bus, ride a Greenstar Express or JAC Liner from Buendia bound for Los Baños.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the safer climbing months. The forest is drier and the limatik are fewer. June to October the leeches are most active and the trail is muddier. The wet season closes the trail during heavy rain; the UPLB forestry office holds the daily call. Weekday climbs are the quietest; the Makiling trail has a daily cap on registration.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Los Baños has the broadest selection of hot-spring resorts and inns near the UPLB area. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g320302-Los_Banos_Laguna_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>The Makiling north trail is the slower, forested side of the mountain. The Mudspring, the canopy, and the hot-spring afternoon make for a long day that earns the climb. For trekkers who want the Makiling forest without the southern trail crowds, this is the calmer call.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Makiling North Trail: Los Banos Climb Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY climb plan for the Mt. Makiling north trail from UPLB Los Banos. Mudspring, forest canopy, hot-spring pairing, transport, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Makiling, Los Banos, Laguna, North Trail, Forest Climb',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'calamba',
