    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 36. MT. MANALMON
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2008/02/mt-manalmon.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Manalmon, Bulacan: A Half-Day Climb with a Cave and a River',
        'slug' => 'mt-manalmon-bulacan-half-day-climb-cave-and-river',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Manalmon in Doña Remedios Trinidad, Bulacan is the half-day climb with a cave stop and a river crossing. Here is the trail, the cave, and the day plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Manalmon sits in Doña Remedios Trinidad (DRT), Bulacan, on the foothills of the Sierra Madre. The mountain is short, around 200 meters at the summit, with a one-hour climb on a wide grass ridge. The standout features are not the summit itself but the trip: a river crossing on a bamboo raft, a small cave stop, and a wide view of the DRT countryside from the top. The total day is around four hours of moving time, which makes Manalmon one of the friendliest beginner climbs in central Luzon.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a single Saturday or Sunday day trip from Manila. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Madlum in DRT. Register at the barangay tourism table, pay the small fee, and the local crew assigns the guide and the raft. The first stop is the river crossing; the Madlum River runs across the trail at the base of the mountain.</p>
<h3>The Bamboo Raft</h3>
<p>The crossing is on a small bamboo raft pulled across the river by a rope. The local crew handles the rope; visitors sit or stand. The crossing takes around 90 seconds. The raft is the friendly version of the river crossing; you stay dry.</p>
<h3>The Madlum Cave Stop</h3>
<p>After the raft, the trail passes the entrance to Madlum Cave. The cave is shallow, you walk in for around 30 meters and out the back. The chamber has stalactites and a small spring pool. The local guide carries a torch.</p>
<h2>The Climb</h2>
<p>From the cave, the climb to Manalmon is around 45 minutes on a wide grass ridge. The grade is moderate, the path is well-worn, and the wind on the ridge keeps the heat down. The summit is a small clearing with a wooden marker and a 360-degree view of the DRT lowland.</p>
<h3>The View</h3>
<p>The view sweeps north into the Sierra Madre, east into the DRT valley, south back to the Madlum river, and west toward Bulacan central. The peak fits maybe 20 trekkers comfortably. Photos and a quick snack, then descend.</p>
<h2>The Optional Mt. Gola Combo</h2>
<p>For groups with extra time, the local crew offers the Mt. Gola side climb. Mt. Gola sits across the river from Manalmon, with a 30-minute climb to a small peak. Combine the two for a full half-day; the round trip is around six hours.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners or walking shoes</li>
<li>Sun hat, sunscreen, and a light long-sleeve sun shirt</li>
<li>Two liters of water</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the summit</li>
<li>A small headlamp for the cave</li>
<li>A waterproof dry bag for the raft crossing</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, raft, and the post-climb merienda</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to DRT</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to the Marilao exit, then the highway north through San Rafael and into DRT. The drive is around two hours from Quezon City. By bus, ride a Baliwag Transit from Cubao bound for San Rafael, then a jeepney to DRT. The Madlum jump-off is along the main DRT road.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the easiest for the river crossing. The water is low and the raft glides smoothly. June to October the river runs higher and the raft may not operate during typhoons; the local crew holds the call. The cogon ridge is comfortable in the cool months. Weekend climbs are popular; the trail can have 100 climbers on a Saturday in January.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most groups do Manalmon as a Manila day trip. For an overnight, the DRT side has small farm stays and the Madlum river area has camping spots. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895131-Bulacan_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Manalmon is the right first climb for beginners. The raft, the cave, and the short ridge to the summit make for a half-day that suits a wider group than the harder climbs. For Manila families and first-time trekkers, this is one of the friendlier picks in central Luzon.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Manalmon Bulacan: Half-Day Climb with Cave | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY half-day climb plan for Mt. Manalmon in DRT, Bulacan. Bamboo raft, Madlum Cave, summit ridge, transport from Manila, and best months.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Manalmon, DRT, Bulacan, Madlum Cave, Beginner Climb',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'bulacan-province',
