    // 37. MT. SUSONG DALAGA
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2009/03/mt-susong-dalaga.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Susong Dalaga, Norzagaray Bulacan: A Short Cogon Climb',
        'slug' => 'mt-susong-dalaga-norzagaray-bulacan-short-cogon-climb',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Susong Dalaga in Norzagaray, Bulacan is the short cogon climb with a wide Sierra Madre view. Here is the trail, the camp option, and the Manila day plan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Susong Dalaga sits in Norzagaray, Bulacan, on the foothills of the southern Sierra Madre. The mountain is short, around 450 meters at the summit, with a one and a half-hour climb on a sun-exposed cogon ridge. The name translates to "young woman's breast" and refers to the rounded shape of the peak from a distance. The trail is the kind that local groups recommend as a stepping stone between Manalmon and the bigger Bulacan climbs.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a half-day climb with a pre-dawn start, a sunrise on the summit, and a late-morning descent. Total trip from Manila is around eight hours including the drive.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. San Lorenzo in Norzagaray. Register at the barangay tourism table, hire a local guide, and start the climb on a farm road that becomes a cogon trail after 20 minutes. The first half hour is moderate grade, the upper half is steeper.</p>
<h3>The Cogon Ridge</h3>
<p>The ridge runs from the lower farm to the summit in a steady climb. The grass is shoulder-high in places. The sun is direct on the path; the pre-dawn start is the only sane plan in the dry months.</p>
<h3>At the Summit</h3>
<p>The peak is a wide grass clearing with a 360-degree view. The Sierra Madre rises to the east, the Bulacan lowland spreads to the west, and on a clear morning the Marikina Valley is visible to the southwest. The clearing fits maybe 20 trekkers.</p>
<h2>The Optional Camp</h2>
<p>For groups that want the overnight version, the summit holds a small flat clearing on the leeward side. Pitch the tent for the sunset and the sunrise the next morning. The camp has no water source; carry up two liters per person.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners with grip for the loose dirt</li>
<li>Sun hat, sunscreen, and a long-sleeve sun shirt for the cogon</li>
<li>Two liters of water for the day climb, three for the overnight</li>
<li>Headlamp for the pre-dawn start</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Tent and warm layer for the overnight</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, and the descent merienda</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Norzagaray</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to the Marilao exit, then the highway north through Sta. Maria and into Norzagaray. The drive is around 90 minutes from Quezon City. By bus, ride a Baliwag Transit from Cubao bound for Norzagaray, then a tricycle to the San Lorenzo jump-off.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to March are the dry, cool months and the safest. The cogon is dry and the trail is firm. April and May the heat builds; the pre-dawn start is mandatory. June to October the cogon turns green and the trail becomes muddier. Avoid the typhoon weeks. Weekend climbs are popular; the trail can have 50 climbers on a Saturday in February.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Most groups do Susong Dalaga as a Manila day trip. For an overnight, Norzagaray has small inns near the town center. The neighboring San Jose del Monte side has more lodge options. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3895131-Bulacan_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Susong Dalaga is the short, exposed Bulacan climb. The cogon ridge, the wide summit view, and the easy Manila day trip make for a good first or second mountain. For trekkers building up to the bigger Bulacan and Rizal climbs, this is the right rung on the ladder.</p>
