    // 38. MT. PINATUBO VIA SAPANG UWAK, PORAC
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2012/03/mt-pinatubo-via-sapang-uwak.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Pinatubo via Sapang Uwak, Porac: The Aeta-Guided Trail Route',
        'slug' => 'mt-pinatubo-via-sapang-uwak-porac-aeta-guided-trail-route',
        'excerpt' => 'The Sapang Uwak trail from Porac is the long-walk Aeta route to Mt. Pinatubo. Here is the calm read on the trek, the camp, and the alternative to the Capas 4x4 trip.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The standard Mt. Pinatubo day trip uses the Capas 4x4 route from Sta. Juliana, Tarlac. The longer, harder, and more rewarding alternative is the Sapang Uwak trail from Porac, Pampanga. The Sapang Uwak route is guided by the Aeta community of Brgy. Sapang Uwak, the indigenous people who lived around the mountain before and after the 1991 eruption. The trek is a two-day trek through lahar canyons and forested ridges to the crater, with a camp on the crater rim. The kwento is the trail itself, the Aeta culture, and the alternative angle on the same crater.</p>
<p>This is the trip for trekkers who want a real hike rather than a 4x4 ride. The total moving time is around eight hours up, six hours down, with a camp at the crater between.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Sapang Uwak in Porac. Register at the barangay tourism table, hire the Aeta guides (mandatory), and start the climb on a wide lahar-bed trail. The first three hours follow the lahar canyon of the Pasig-Potrero River.</p>
<h3>The Lahar Canyons</h3>
<p>The canyon walls rise on both sides in pink and grey ash deposits from the 1991 eruption. The trail crosses the river several times in shallow sections. The lahar bed is the visual signature of the trail; the route looks like a different planet.</p>
<h3>The Forest Belt</h3>
<p>Past the lahar, the trail enters a recovering secondary forest. The Aeta community replanted parts of this area after the eruption. The canopy holds the heat off and the trail is well-shaded for around two hours. The bird sounds are constant.</p>
<h3>The Crater Rim Camp</h3>
<p>The camp is on a small flat clearing near the crater rim. The site has tree cover and a small spring for water. Pitch the tent on the leeward side; the wind across the crater picks up at night.</p>
<h2>The Crater Lake at Dawn</h2>
<p>Wake at 5 a.m. Walk the short trail to the crater rim by 5:30 a.m. The sky lightens over the lake and the inner crater walls catch the first light. The lake is a sulfur green with a deeper blue at the center, the same lake the Capas day-trippers see, but from the opposite rim and with no crowd in sight. The morning at the crater is the kind of moment that pays back the long approach.</p>
<h2>The Aeta Cultural Note</h2>
<p>The Aeta community runs the trail because the mountain is their ancestral land. Respect the protocols: no loud music, no rocks taken as souvenirs, no swimming in the crater lake (the gas releases from the lake bed are unpredictable, the same warning as the Capas side). Tip the guides at the end of the trek; the rate is set by the community.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent and ground sheet, the camp is at high elevation</li>
<li>Warm layer for the night, the crater rim cools to 18 degrees</li>
<li>Trail runners or hiking shoes with grip for the lahar and the forest</li>
<li>Four liters of water for the climb up, the camp spring refills</li>
<li>Stove and food for one dinner and one breakfast</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>A buff for the lahar dust on the first day</li>
<li>Cash for registration, the Aeta guides, and the post-trek meal in Porac</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Sapang Uwak</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to the Dau exit, then the highway south through Angeles and into Porac. From Porac town, the road to Sapang Uwak is signposted; a habal-habal (motorcycle) is the local transport from the town to the barangay. Total trip from Manila is around three hours by car. By bus, ride a Victory Liner or Five Star bus from Cubao bound for Dau, then transfer to a Porac jeep.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the only safe window. The river crossings in the lahar are shallow and the camp at the crater is comfortable. June to October the trail closes during typhoons because the river crossings become impassable. The summer months (March to May) bring hot lahar dust; pack the buff and the long-sleeve sun shirt. The Aeta tourism office has a daily cap on permits; book ahead.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay Before and After</h2>
<p>Angeles City has the broader hotel selection for the Pinatubo area base. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g320304-Angeles_City_Pampanga_Province_Central_Luzon_Region_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Clark is 20 minutes from Angeles for an airport-adjacent base.</p>
<p>The Sapang Uwak trail is the long-walk version of the Pinatubo trip. The lahar canyons, the forest, the Aeta culture, and the camp on the crater rim add up to a two-day trek that the Capas day-trippers never see. For trekkers tired of the 4x4 crowd, this is the calm alternative.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Pinatubo via Sapang Uwak Porac: Aeta Trail Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A DIY two-day Aeta-guided trek plan for Mt. Pinatubo via Sapang Uwak, Porac. Lahar canyons, crater rim camp, transport, and the alternative to the Capas 4x4.',
        'tags' => 'Mt. Pinatubo, Sapang Uwak, Porac, Pampanga, Aeta Trail, Trek',
