    // 39. MT. BANOI TRAVERSE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2014/01/mt-banoi-batangas.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Mountaineer',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt. Banoi Traverse, Lobo Batangas: A Quiet Coastal Ridge Climb',
        'slug' => 'mt-banoi-traverse-lobo-batangas-quiet-coastal-ridge-climb',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt. Banoi in Lobo, Batangas is the quieter traverse climb on the southeastern coast. Here is the trail, the ridge, and the Verde Passage view.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt. Banoi sits in Lobo, Batangas, on the same southeastern coastal range as Mt. Lobo. The mountain is around 970 meters at the summit, taller than its neighbor Lobo, with a longer trail and a real traverse option that connects the Lobo side to the Banoi side via a ridge walk. The trail is the climb that few Manila trekkers know; the trail head is harder to reach, the local guide pool is smaller, and the route demands an early start. For trekkers tired of the busier southern Luzon climbs, Banoi is the quiet pick.</p>
<p>The standard plan is a long single-day climb or a Saturday-overnight with a camp on the summit ridge. Total moving time is around six to seven hours up, four hours down, on the Lobo-side approach.</p>
<h2>The Trail in Brief</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Pinaghawanan in Lobo, around 30 minutes inland from the Lobo town center. Register at the barangay tourism table, hire a local guide, and start the climb on a coconut grove farm road that runs flat for the first hour.</p>
<h3>The Forest Section</h3>
<p>Past the coconut grove, the trail climbs through a secondary forest for around three hours. The canopy is thick, the trail is rooty but well-shaded, and the bird sounds carry through. The middle of the forest holds a small stream where you can refill water.</p>
<h3>The Summit Ridge</h3>
<p>The last hour of the climb runs along a ridge with the first sea views opening to the south. The Verde Island Passage spreads to the south, the Lobo coast to the east, and the Mindoro silhouette across the strait on a clear day. The grass on the ridge is calf-high; the wind picks up steady.</p>
<h3>At the Summit</h3>
<p>The summit is a wide grass clearing at 970 meters. The view sweeps the southeastern Luzon coast, the Verde Passage, and the Mindoro coast. The clearing fits 15 trekkers comfortably; the overnight camp uses the leeward side.</p>
<h2>The Traverse Option</h2>
<p>For groups doing the traverse, the route descends from Banoi to the Mt. Lobo summit via a connecting ridge, then back down the standard Lobo trail to Brgy. Sawang. The traverse adds three hours of moving time. Coordinate the traverse with the local guides; the route requires a one-way pickup at the Lobo-side jump-off.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Trail runners with deep lugs for the rooty forest</li>
<li>Sun hat and a long-sleeve sun shirt for the ridge</li>
<li>Three liters of water for the day climb, four for the overnight</li>
<li>Tent and warm layer for the overnight</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>Light packed lunch for the summit</li>
<li>Light rain layer, the coastal weather changes fast</li>
<li>Cash for registration, guide, traverse pickup, and the Lobo restaurant meal</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Pinaghawanan</h2>
<p>From Manila, take SLEX to the STAR Tollway, exit at Batangas City, then drive east through Lipa and into Lobo. From Lobo town, the road to Brgy. Pinaghawanan is signposted. The drive is around three hours from Quezon City. By bus, ride a JAM Liner or DLTB from Buendia to Batangas City, then a jeepney bound for Lobo.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May are the dry months and the safer climbing window. The forest is comfortable and the ridge is dry. June to October the trail becomes muddier and the ridge gets exposed to the habagat winds. Avoid the typhoon weeks. The summer months (March to May) bring strong sun on the ridge; pack extra water.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The Laiya beach row 45 minutes north has the broader resort selection. Lobo town has small inns near the coast. The Malabrigo lighthouse area is a 20-minute drive from the climb. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g7287321-San_Juan_Batangas_Province_Calabarzon_Luzon-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p>
<p>Banoi is the quieter Batangas summit. The forest, the coastal ridge, and the Verde Passage view make for a calm day that pays back the long drive. For trekkers who already logged Lobo and want the bigger sibling, Banoi is the right step up.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt. Banoi Traverse Lobo Batangas: Climb Plan | Resort Guru PH',
