<p>Mt. Apo is the highest peak in the Philippines at 2,956 meters. The mountain has several trail routes; the Kidapawan and Kapatagan trails are the most popular northern and western approaches. The Sta. Cruz trail is the southern approach, starting from Brgy. Sibulan in Sta. Cruz, Davao del Sur. The trail is the longer, less crowded route, with a camp at Lake Venado on the second night and a summit push on the third morning. The kwento is the long forest, the cool lake, and the wide summit panorama.</p>
<p>This is the climb that requires preparation. The trail is rated hard, the total moving time is around 18 hours across three days, and the elevation gain is over 2,000 meters from the trailhead to the summit. The Sta. Cruz tourism office requires a medical clearance, a registered guide, and a permit booked in advance.</p>
<h2>Day One: Trailhead to Camp 1</h2>
<p>The jump-off is at Brgy. Sibulan in Sta. Cruz. Register at the tourism office, present the medical clearance, hire the registered guide, and start the climb on a wide farm road. The first three hours climb through a tropical forest with the canopy holding the heat off.</p>
<h3>The Tinikaran Springs</h3>
<p>The first major water source is at the Tinikaran Springs, around three hours up. The water is cold and clean; refill bottles here. The springs sit at around 1,500 meters elevation.</p>
<h3>Camp 1</h3>
<p>The standard Day 1 camp is at the Tinikaran area, around 1,600 meters. The clearing is small but flat. The night is cool, around 14 to 16 degrees Celsius.</p>
<h2>Day Two: Camp 1 to Lake Venado</h2>
<p>Day 2 climbs through the mossy forest belt to the Lake Venado camp. The mossy forest is the signature of Apo's middle slopes; the trees are thick with moss, the ground is mossy, and the light is filtered green. The climb takes around six hours from Camp 1 to Lake Venado.</p>
<h3>Lake Venado</h3>
<p>Lake Venado sits at 2,200 meters elevation, a wide shallow lake at the base of the Apo summit cone. The camp is on the lake's southern shore. The site is open, the wind picks up at night, and the temperature drops to 8 to 10 degrees by midnight. The lake itself dries up in the peak summer months but holds water from November to May.</p>
<h2>Day Three: Lake Venado to the Summit and Down</h2>
<p>Wake at 3 a.m. on Day 3. The summit push from Lake Venado takes around three hours on a steep boulder-and-sulfur-vent trail. The boulder field is the test; the rocks are loose, the slope is steep, and the air at 2,800 meters thins noticeably.</p>
<h3>The Summit</h3>
<p>The summit of Mt. Apo is a wide plateau with a small marker and a 360-degree view. The Davao Gulf opens to the east, the South Cotabato lowland to the south, the Mindanao interior to the north, and Sarangani to the southwest. The plateau holds 50 trekkers comfortably; on the peak days from January to April it can be busier.</p>
<h3>The Descent</h3>
<p>From the summit, the standard descent goes back to Lake Venado, packs up the camp, and continues down to Tinikaran or back to the Sibulan trailhead. Total Day 3 moving time is around 10 hours.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<ul>
<li>Tent with a strong rain fly and ground sheet</li>
<li>Warm jacket, a wool layer, and a beanie</li>
<li>Sleeping bag rated for 5 degrees Celsius or lower</li>
<li>Trail-running shoes with deep lugs and an extra pair</li>
<li>Three liters of water capacity, refill at Tinikaran and Venado</li>
<li>Stove and food for two dinners and three breakfasts</li>
<li>Headlamp with spare batteries</li>
<li>Light rain layer and a wind-shell</li>
<li>Trekking poles for the descent</li>
<li>Medical clearance, ID, and cash for the permit, guide, and Sta. Cruz meal</li>
</ul>
<h2>Getting to Sta. Cruz</h2>
<p>Fly to Davao with <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> or <a href="https://www.philippineairlines.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Philippine Airlines</a>. From Davao city, the drive to Sta. Cruz is around two hours south along the Davao del Sur coastal highway. The Sibulan trailhead is a 30-minute habal-habal ride from the Sta. Cruz town center.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to May are the dry months and the standard climbing window. The trail is firm and the summit is the clearest. November to February the climb is colder but still doable. June to October the climb closes during typhoons because the trail becomes impassable. The Sta. Cruz tourism office sets the daily quota; book the permit at least one month ahead. Avoid Holy Week, the trail caps out.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay Before and After</h2>
<p>Davao city has the broadest hotel selection for the post-climb base. Compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298459-Davao_City_Davao_del_Sur_Province_Davao_Region_Mindanao-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. For a quieter pre-climb night, Sta. Cruz town has small inns.</p>
<p>The Sta. Cruz trail is the long, quiet, southern way up Mt. Apo. The mossy forest, the Lake Venado camp, and the summit at 2,956 meters add up to the kind of climb that earns its place on a Filipino trekker's bucket list. For climbers tired of the Kidapawan crowds, this is the alternative that pays back the longer approach.</p>
